% ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
% ABSTRACT
% ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

\noindent
\fcolorbox{primaryblue!80}{lightgray!30}{%
    \parbox{0.95\textwidth}{%
        \vspace{0.5em}%
        {\large\bfseries\textcolor{primaryblue!80}{Abstract}}\\[0.8em]%
        \small
        Music-brain mapping research remains fragmented across isolated findings and disparate theoretical frameworks. We conducted a systematic review and coordinate-based meta-analysis of 448 neuroimaging and behavioral studies across nine cognitive units. Four core units (\Cthree{}) with sufficient data for meta-analysis demonstrated distinct neural substrates and effect sizes: \SPU{} (pooled \cohend{0.84} [0.44--1.24]), \STU{} (pooled \cohend{0.67} [0.52--0.82]), \IMU{} (pooled \cohend{0.53} [0.42--0.65]), and \ARU{} (pooled \cohend{0.83} [0.61--1.05]). Cross-unit pathway analysis identified five high-confidence pathways, including consonance$\rightarrow$pleasure (\correlation{0.81--0.84}) and beat$\rightarrow$motor synchronization (\correlation{0.70}). The \Cthree{} framework provides the first comprehensive, empirically grounded, and computationally testable model of musical cognition, integrating spectral, temporal, mnemonic, and affective processing with explicit neural substrates and functional interactions.

        \vspace{0.5em}
        \noindent\textbf{Keywords:} \textit{music cognition; meta-analysis; auditory processing; emotion; memory; predictive coding; computational neuroscience}\\[0.8em]
        \noindent\makebox[0.95\textwidth]{\textcolor{primaryblue!80}{\rule{\textwidth}{16pt}}}
    }%
}

\vspace{0.8em}

