% ============================================================================
% 1. INTRODUCTION
% ============================================================================

\section{Introduction}

Music is a universal human phenomenon that engages virtually every region of the brain, from peripheral auditory processing to the highest levels of cognitive and affective function \citep{zatorre2007, koelsch2014}. Despite decades of neuroscientific investigation, our understanding of how the brain transforms acoustic input into rich musical experiences---including rhythm perception, melodic encoding, emotional responses, and memory formation---remains fragmented across isolated findings and competing theoretical frameworks.

\vspace{-0.3em}
\subsection{The Fragmentation Problem}
\vspace{-0.2em}

The current landscape of music neuroscience is characterized by several critical limitations. First, studies typically examine single dimensions of musical processing (e.g., pitch perception, rhythmic entrainment, or emotional responses) without integrating findings across domains. Second, divergent methodological approaches---including functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI), electroencephalography (EEG), magnetoencephalography (MEG), and behavioral paradigms---yield results that are difficult to synthesize quantitatively. Third, existing theoretical models tend to emphasize either bottom-up acoustic feature extraction or top-down predictive processing, rarely bridging these perspectives.

\textbf{Gap Analysis: Existing Meta-Analyses.} While several meta-analyses have examined specific domains of music cognition, none have provided a comprehensive synthesis integrating all major cognitive dimensions. Previous meta-analyses include: (1) \textbf{Emotion-focused:} Koelsch (2014) reviewed music-evoked emotions but focused primarily on reward and affective processing, without systematic effect size quantification or cross-domain integration; (2) \textbf{Rhythm-focused:} Grahn \& Brett (2007) examined beat perception but limited to sensorimotor timing, excluding memory and affective dimensions; (3) \textbf{Pitch-focused:} Zatorre \& Belin (2001) reviewed pitch processing but did not integrate with temporal or emotional processing; (4) \textbf{Clinical-focused:} Several meta-analyses examined music therapy outcomes but lacked neural mechanism detail. \textbf{Critical gap:} No existing meta-analysis has: (a) systematically quantified effect sizes across all major cognitive dimensions; (b) integrated spectral, temporal, mnemonic, and affective processing within a unified framework; (c) provided cross-unit pathway analysis with quantitative effect sizes; (d) employed comprehensive quality assessment and publication bias correction across all domains. The present work addresses this gap by providing the first comprehensive, quantitatively grounded synthesis of music-brain relationships across all major cognitive dimensions.

This fragmentation impedes both basic scientific understanding and clinical translation. Without a unified framework, it remains challenging to: (1) generate testable predictions that span multiple processing levels; (2) identify the neural mechanisms underlying individual differences in musical ability and preference; and (3) develop targeted music-based interventions for neurological and psychiatric conditions.

\vspace{-0.3em}
\subsection{A Systematic Approach: The \Cthree{} Framework}
\vspace{-0.2em}

To address these limitations, we introduce the Cognitive Consonance Circuit (\Cthree{}) framework---the \textbf{first comprehensive, hierarchically organized model} of music-brain relationships grounded in systematic meta-analysis that integrates all major cognitive dimensions of musical processing. This framework represents the largest and most systematic synthesis of music neuroscience evidence to date, encompassing 448 studies, 1,116 empirical claims, and 574 effect sizes across nine specialized processing units. The \Cthree{} framework conceptualizes musical cognition as emerging from the coordinated activity of \textbf{nine specialized processing units}, each characterized by distinct neural substrates, computational operations, and representational formats:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*, topsep=0pt, itemsep=0pt]
    \item \textbf{Spectral Processing Unit (\SPU{})}: Pitch, timbre, and harmonic relationships
    \item \textbf{Sensorimotor Timing Unit (\STU{})}: Temporal structure, beat induction, auditory-motor coupling
    \item \textbf{Integrative Memory Unit (\IMU{})}: Musical memory encoding, consolidation, and retrieval
    \item \textbf{Affective Resonance Unit (\ARU{})}: Emotional responses and reward processing
    \item \textbf{Auditory Salience Unit (\ASU{})}: Attention and salience detection
    \item \textbf{Motor Planning Unit (\MPU{})}: Motor preparation and execution
    \item \textbf{Novelty Detection Unit (\NDU{})}: Unexpected event detection
    \item \textbf{Predictive Coding Unit (\PCU{})}: Expectation and prediction error
    \item \textbf{Reward Processing Unit (\RPU{})}: Anticipation and reward prediction
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Analytical Strategy: Comprehensive Framework, Focused Meta-Analysis.} While the complete \Cthree{} framework encompasses all nine units, we employ a \textbf{two-tier analytical strategy} to balance comprehensiveness with methodological rigor: (1) \textbf{Full framework synthesis:} All nine units are included in qualitative synthesis, brain region mapping, pathway identification, and theoretical model development (91 models total); (2) \textbf{Focused meta-analysis:} Quantitative meta-analysis is restricted to the four core units (\SPU{}, \STU{}, \IMU{}, \ARU{}) that meet minimum methodological thresholds for reliable pooling ($k \geq 10$ effect sizes after quality filtering, sufficient statistical reporting). This strategy provides three key advantages: (a) \textbf{Reduced heterogeneity:} Focusing on well-studied units with consistent methodologies minimizes between-study variance and improves meta-analytic precision; (b) \textbf{Methodological rigor:} Core-4 units have sufficient sample sizes ($k$=13--60) for stable random-effects models, prediction intervals, and publication bias assessment; (c) \textbf{Comprehensive coverage:} The full nine-unit framework ensures no important cognitive domain is overlooked, while descriptive statistics for smaller units (ASU, MPU, NDU, PCU, RPU) provide preliminary evidence for future meta-analyses as literature expands.

The four core units selected for meta-analysis are:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*, topsep=0pt, itemsep=0pt]
    \item \textbf{Spectral Processing Unit (\SPU{})}: Extraction and representation of pitch, timbre, and harmonic relationships from acoustic input
    \item \textbf{Sensorimotor Timing Unit (\STU{})}: Temporal structure encoding, beat induction, and auditory-motor coupling
    \item \textbf{Integrative Memory Unit (\IMU{})}: Encoding, consolidation, and retrieval of musical memories in autobiographical context
    \item \textbf{Affective Resonance Unit (\ARU{})}: Generation and modulation of emotional responses to music, including reward processing
\end{enumerate}

Together, these four units account for 88\% of the empirical literature (405 of 448 papers) and provide a robust foundation for understanding the core mechanisms of musical experience.



