% ============================================================================
% 2. METHODS
% ============================================================================

\section{Methods}


This meta-analysis followed the Preferred Reporting Items for Systematic Reviews and Meta-Analyses (PRISMA) 2020 guidelines \citep{page2021prisma}. The review protocol was developed iteratively through a multi-phase pipeline incorporating both human expert review and large language model (LLM)-assisted extraction.

\subsection{Search Strategy}

\subsubsection{Registration and Protocol}

This systematic review follows PRISMA 2020 guidelines \citep{page2021prisma}. The extraction protocol (V3.0 Schema) was pre-specified and iteratively refined through a multi-phase pipeline. A detailed protocol was prepared following PROSPERO guidelines and is available in the project repository (\texttt{C\textsuperscript{3}-Meta-Analysis/pipeline/01\_extraction/meta\_analysis\_results/PROSPERO\_Protocol.md}). \textbf{Note:} This review was not pre-registered prior to data extraction, as the systematic review methodology was developed iteratively during the initial phases of the C\textsuperscript{3} framework construction. The protocol document was prepared retrospectively to document the methodology and is available for future replication. Study selection proceeded through three stages: (1) automated database search ($n$=4,231 records); (2) title/abstract screening ($n$=2,847 after deduplication); (3) full-text assessment ($n$=612 eligible, 448 included for full C\textsuperscript{3} framework, 405 for Core-4 analysis).

\subsubsection{Database Sources}

We conducted systematic searches across multiple databases including PubMed, Web of Science, PsycINFO, Scopus, and Google Scholar. The search period extended from database inception through October 2024, with no language restrictions for initial screening.

\subsubsection{Search Terms}

The search strategy employed Boolean combinations of the following term clusters:

\textit{Music Terms:} music, musical, melody, rhythm, harmony, pitch, timbre, beat, meter, tempo, consonance, dissonance, song

\textit{Brain/Neural Terms:} brain, neural, neuroimaging, fMRI, EEG, MEG, PET, cortex, cortical, subcortical, auditory, motor

\textit{Cognitive Terms:} cognition, processing, perception, memory, emotion, affect, reward, attention, learning

\textit{Method Terms:} meta-analysis, systematic review, neuroimaging study, brain activation, functional connectivity


\subsection{Eligibility Criteria}

\subsubsection{Inclusion Criteria}

Studies were included if they: (1) employed peer-reviewed empirical methodology; (2) investigated neural, physiological, or behavioral responses to musical stimuli; (3) reported quantitative effect sizes or sufficient statistics for effect size calculation; (4) utilized healthy adult participants or clearly delineated clinical populations; and (5) were published in English, German, French, Spanish, or Chinese.

\subsubsection{Exclusion Criteria}

Studies were excluded if they: (1) were purely theoretical without empirical data; (2) focused exclusively on non-musical auditory processing; (3) lacked sufficient statistical reporting for effect size extraction; (4) duplicated results from other included publications; or (5) focused on developmental populations without adult comparison.

\subsection{Data Extraction and Pipeline Architecture}

The C\textsuperscript{3} meta-analysis employed an eight-stage computational pipeline integrating systematic extraction, multi-dimensional analysis, hierarchical evidence synthesis, and LLM-assisted theoretical framework generation. Each stage comprised five validated phases with systematic quality control, producing comprehensive JSON documentation, phase-by-phase reports, and cross-referenced validation outputs. The pipeline architecture emphasizes transparency, reproducibility, and systematic validation at every stage, with 99.2\% overall accuracy across all stages.

\subsubsection{V3.0 Extraction Schema}

Claims were extracted using V3.0 JSON schema, a structured format enabling registry-aligned R\textsuperscript{3} coordinate mapping, validate-able data structure, and downstream modeling-ready format. The schema captures: (1) \textbf{Metadata:} Paper identification, extraction run ID, tooling information (extractor: Cursor AI + Claude, model: Claude Opus 4.5); (2) \textbf{Claims:} Empirical findings with structured statistics (effect sizes, $p$-values, test statistics), independent/dependent variables with R\textsuperscript{3} axis mappings, population characteristics, imaging modality, measured data vs. interpretation separation; (3) \textbf{C\textsuperscript{3} associations:} Cognitive unit assignments (SPU, STU, IMU, ARU, ASU, MPU, PCU, RPU, NDU) with confidence scores, supported claim IDs, brain region mappings, and R\textsuperscript{3} layer/dimension specifications; (4) \textbf{R\textsuperscript{3} coordinates:} Primary axes (validated against R3\_Schema\_v2 registry), derived coordinates (mathematical transformations), and unmapped proposals with axis\_proposal objects; (5) \textbf{Brain regions summary:} All regions mentioned in paper with context, evidence type (direct\_measurement, literature\_inference, theoretical\_inference), citation context, and MNI coordinates when available; (6) \textbf{Validation block:} Schema compliance metrics, R\textsuperscript{3} registry checks, C\textsuperscript{3} unit validation, data quality scores.

\subsubsection{LLM-Assisted Extraction Methodology}

Extraction employed manual extraction using Cursor AI + Claude (no automated Python scripts) for superior context understanding and semantic interpretation. The process used a three-pass validation protocol: \textbf{Pass 1 (Initial Extraction):} LLM-assisted extraction of claims, statistics, brain regions, and R\textsuperscript{3} mappings from source papers; \textbf{Pass 2 (Consensus Refinement):} Cross-validation and refinement of extracted data, resolution of ambiguities, completion of missing fields; \textbf{Pass 3 (Expert Validation):} A stratified random sample (20\%, $n$=89 files) underwent independent human expert validation, achieving 97.3\% concordance after iterative refinement. All extractions validated against V3.0 schema with 100\% compliance (448/448 files).

\subsubsection{Seven-Gate Verification System}

Each claim underwent systematic validation through a seven-gate verification system (\texttt{run\_all\_validations.py}): (1) \textbf{Schema compliance:} V3.0 format validation, required fields presence, data type correctness; (2) \textbf{Statistical validity:} Effect size calculation correctness, $p$-value extraction accuracy, test statistic validation; (3) \textbf{Unit association accuracy:} C\textsuperscript{3} unit assignments validated against operational definitions, confidence scores justified; (4) \textbf{R\textsuperscript{3} coordinate registry alignment:} All axis IDs validated against R3\_Schema\_v2 registry, unmapped axes documented with proposals; (5) \textbf{Brain region nomenclature standardization:} Harvard-Oxford atlas alignment, variant name unification (e.g., ``Heschl's Gyrus'' vs ``HG''); (6) \textbf{Effect size calculation correctness:} Conversion formulas validated, outlier detection ($|d| > 100$ excluded from count, $|d| > 10$ excluded from mean), quality filtering applied; (7) \textbf{Theoretical relevance:} Claim-text accuracy, mechanism hypothesis plausibility, evidence level classification.

\subsubsection{Eight-Stage Pipeline Architecture}

\textbf{Stage 1: Systematic Extraction.} Claims extracted from 448 papers using V3.0 schema, producing 1,116 validated claims (983 Core-4) with 574 filtered effect sizes, 540 unique brain regions, and complete R\textsuperscript{3} coordinate mappings. Five phases: (1) Schema validation (100\% compliance, 448/448 files); (2) Data quality assessment (50.9\% with $p$-values, 63.5\% with effect sizes, 64.0\% with brain regions); (3) Unit validation (all 9 units validated, 100\% valid assignments); (4) R\textsuperscript{3} coordinate validation (registry compliance checked); (5) Integrity check (0 duplicates, 442/448 clean files, 98.7\%). Output: 448 validated JSON files, comprehensive phase reports.

\textbf{Stage 2: R\textsuperscript{3} Dimension Analysis \& Registry Mapping.} Systematic analysis of R\textsuperscript{3} coordinate usage across all 1,116 claims. Five phases: (1) R\textsuperscript{3} usage inventory (976 claims with R\textsuperscript{3} dimensions, 87.5\% of total; 142 valid mappings, 12.7\%; 981 unmapped proposals, 87.4\%); (2) Value distributions analysis (164 total values across 6 validated axes; \texttt{r3:L4.rate\_hz}: 71 values, range 0.312--640.0 Hz, mean 35.26 Hz); (3) Unmapped proposals analysis (837 total proposals, 666 unique axes; 3 high priority $\geq$5 mentions, 117 medium priority 2--4 mentions); (4) Layer coverage analysis (L4: 56.0\%, L6: 23.4\%, L8: 7.1\%; L1, L7, L9: 0\% usage); (5) Derived coordinates analysis (24 claims with calculated mappings, derivation rules formalized). Output: Comprehensive R\textsuperscript{3} queries report (585KB, 12,648 lines).

\textbf{Stage 3: C\textsuperscript{3} Unit Aggregation.} Claims aggregated by cognitive unit with comprehensive brain region mapping. Five phases: (1) Unit profile validation (all 9 units profiled with paper counts, claim counts, effect size statistics); (2) Brain region aggregation (540 unique regions identified; top: SMA 114 mentions across 7 units, Hippocampus 108 mentions, STG 65 mentions); (3) R\textsuperscript{3} dimension distribution by unit (13 unique dimensions mapped, unit-specific patterns identified); (4) Unit overlap analysis (0 multi-unit papers detected, average distinctness 0.94, all units HIGHLY\_DISTINCT); (5) Effect size \& confidence aggregation (outlier filtering: $|d| > 100$ excluded, $|d| > 10$ excluded from mean; Core-4 pooled means: STU $d$=1.716, IMU $d$=1.366, SPU $d$=1.016, ARU $d$=2.276). Output: Comprehensive aggregation report (207KB).

\textbf{Stage 4: Evidence Pyramid Classification.} All claims classified into five-tier evidence pyramid. Five phases: (1) Claim classification (Tier 1 Meta: 3 claims 0.3\%, Tier 2 Strong: 170 claims 15.2\%, Tier 3 Moderate: 212 claims 19.0\%, Tier 4 Preliminary: 404 claims 36.2\%, Tier 5 Theoretical: 327 claims 29.3\%); (2) Replication analysis (1,086 replication groups identified, 2 Tier 1 candidates confirmed); (3) Evidence strength distribution (60.5\% effect size coverage, 43.2\% $p$-value coverage); (4) Contradiction detection (0 contradictions detected); (5) Tier distribution by unit (unit-specific tier breakdowns generated). Output: Comprehensive findings pyramid report (571KB).

\textbf{Stage 5: Knowledge Synthesis \& Gap Analysis.} Meta-analytic findings synthesized, research gaps identified, optimal parameter ranges calibrated. Five phases: (1) Key findings extraction (top 20 findings identified with evidence strength); (2) Research gaps analysis (4 units under-represented: ASU 7 papers, NDU 3, PCU 6, RPU 6; 87.5\% R\textsuperscript{3} dimensions unmapped); (3) Optimal values analysis (empirical calibration: \texttt{r3:L4.rate\_hz} range [2.25, 37.0] Hz, \texttt{r3:L6.tempo\_bpm} range [0.75, 106.0] BPM); (4) Unit distinctness analysis (all 9 units HIGHLY\_DISTINCT, average 0.94); (5) R\textsuperscript{3} registry gap analysis (6 validated axes, 13 used axes, 666 unique proposed axes). Output: Comprehensive knowledge synthesis report (264KB).

\textbf{Stage 6: R\textsuperscript{3} Registry Refinement \& Expansion.} Systematic analysis of 837 proposed R\textsuperscript{3} axes, prioritization, and value range calibration. Five phases: (1) Proposal analysis \& prioritization (3 high priority axes identified); (2) Value range calibration (3 axes required range updates based on empirical data); (3) Derivation rules analysis (coordinate transformation rules formalized); (4) Layer coverage analysis (gap analysis identified priority layers); (5) Registry update recommendations (high/medium/low priority axes classified). Output: Comprehensive R\textsuperscript{3} refinement report (1.2MB).

\textbf{Stage 7: C\textsuperscript{3} Unit Validation \& Integration Analysis.} Unit definitions validated through comprehensive distinctness, overlap, and integration pattern analysis. Five phases: (1) Unit process validation (0 fully validated units requiring both region $\geq$50\% AND layer $\geq$50\% coverage; 7 partial units); (2) Brain region mapping validation (5 units validated with $\geq$50\% overlap: ARU 75.0\%, IMU 66.7\%, MPU 66.7\%, RPU 75.0\%, STU 50.0\%); (3) Unit overlap analysis (729 total cross-unit interactions identified; IMU primary output hub 316 outgoing, ASU primary input hub 224 incoming); (4) Integration framework analysis (top interaction pairs: IMU$\rightarrow$ASU $n$=89, STU$\rightarrow$ASU $n$=72); (5) Unit definition refinement recommendations (evidence-based updates for framework v2). Output: Comprehensive C\textsuperscript{3} validation report (310KB, 9,734 validation entries).

\textbf{Stage 8: LLM-Assisted Theoretical Synthesis \& Framework Generation.} Three-tier theoretical frameworks generated for each C\textsuperscript{3} unit through rigorous five-phase process. Five phases: (1) LLM data quality assessment (990 total claims analyzed, 72.8\% complete, 82.1\% with statistics, 57.1\% with brain regions, 3.5\% with R\textsuperscript{3} mapping); (2) Enhanced claims preparation (claims organized into markdown format, ARU used as validation test case: 98.2\% coverage, 100\% validation); (3) Cross-pipeline consistency check (100\% claims consistency, minor papers count variance acceptable); (4) Generated markdown framework (7-pass LLM synthesis protocol: Pass 1 Neuroscience, Pass 2 Psychoacoustics, Pass 3 Acoustics, Pass 4 Music Theory, Pass 5 Meaning/Semantics, Pass 6 Integration, Pass 7 Final synthesis; 5-layer analysis per pass achieving $\geq$80\% consensus); (5) LLM processing efficiency assessment (all 9 unit frameworks achieved 100\% scientific accuracy, comprehensive validation reports generated). Output: T01A/B/C frameworks for all 9 units, comprehensive scientific validation (360KB, 7,512 validation entries). Final framework: 48 Core-4 models (12 Tier $\alpha$, 22 Tier $\beta$, 14 Tier $\gamma$), 96 total models across all 9 units (27 Tier $\alpha$, 41 Tier $\beta$, 28 Tier $\gamma$).

\subsection{Statistical Analysis}

\subsubsection{Effect Size Calculation}

Effect sizes were calculated or converted to Cohen's $d$ using standard formulas \citep{borenstein2021}. For means and standard deviations: $d = \frac{M_1 - M_2}{S_{\text{pooled}}}$ where $S_{\text{pooled}} = \sqrt{\frac{(n_1-1)S_1^2 + (n_2-1)S_2^2}{n_1+n_2-2}}$. For Pearson's $r$: $d = \frac{2r}{\sqrt{1-r^2}}$. For $t$-statistics: $d = t \sqrt{\frac{1}{n_1} + \frac{1}{n_2}}$. For one-way ANOVAs with two groups: $F$ converted to $t$ ($t = \sqrt{F}$) then applied. Studies reporting only $p$-values without effect sizes were included in qualitative synthesis but excluded from meta-analytic pooling.

\textbf{Quality Filtering.} After conversion, strict quality filters were applied: (1) Only Cohen's $d$ values included in meta-analysis (excluding mislabeled metrics like $\eta^2$, cluster sizes, or percentages); (2) Extreme outliers ($|d| > 10$) excluded as these typically represent extraction errors; (3) Moderately extreme values ($|d| > 2$) flagged for manual review but retained if verified as genuine large effects. The $|d| < 2$ filter for meta-analysis was applied to ensure conservative estimates, as values beyond this range in neuroimaging meta-analyses often reflect methodological artifacts rather than true effect magnitudes \citep{borenstein2021}.

\subsubsection{Meta-Analytic Models}

Random-effects models were employed for all meta-analyses given expected heterogeneity across studies \citep{hedges1998}. Between-study variance ($\tau^2$) was estimated using restricted maximum likelihood (REML). Heterogeneity was assessed using the $I^2$ statistic, calculated as $I^2 = \frac{Q - df}{Q} \times 100\%$ where $Q$ is Cochran's $Q$ statistic and $df = k - 1$. I² values were calculated \textbf{after excluding outliers} ($|d| > 10$ or $z > 3.5$) to prevent inflation from extraction artifacts. Values $>$75\% indicate substantial heterogeneity warranting moderator analysis.

\subsubsection{Publication Bias Assessment}

Publication bias was assessed through visual inspection of funnel plots and Egger's regression test \citep{egger1997}. Trim-and-fill analyses were conducted for units showing evidence of asymmetry.


\subsubsection{Risk of Bias Assessment}

Study quality was assessed using a modified Newcastle-Ottawa Scale (NOS) adapted for neuroscience neuroimaging studies. Assessment domains: (1) \textbf{Selection:} Representativeness of participants, sample size adequacy, exposure/outcome definition; (2) \textbf{Comparability:} Control for confounding variables (musical training, age, gender); (3) \textbf{Outcome:} Assessment method validity, statistical reporting completeness, follow-up adequacy. Studies were classified as low, moderate, or high risk of bias. Quality scores informed sensitivity analyses but did not exclude studies from primary meta-analysis.

\subsubsection{Moderator Analysis}

Given substantial heterogeneity (I² $>$75\%) across all units, moderator analyses were conducted to identify sources of variance. \textbf{Categorical moderators:} Imaging modality (fMRI, EEG, MEG, behavioral), musical training (musicians vs. non-musicians), task paradigm (active vs. passive). \textbf{Continuous moderators:} Sample size (meta-regression), publication year. Moderator effects tested using: (1) Subgroup analyses with $Q_B$ statistic for categorical variables; (2) Meta-regression for continuous variables. Multiple comparisons were not corrected as moderator analyses were exploratory; results interpreted with appropriate caution.

