\vspace{-0.2em}
The four core units selected for meta-analysis (\SPU{}, \STU{}, \IMU{}, \ARU{}) comprised 405 studies (90\% of total) with 983 claims and 574 effect sizes. These units were selected based on: (a) sufficient sample sizes ($k$=13--60 after filtering); (b) consistent methodological approaches enabling reliable pooling; (c) comprehensive statistical reporting (effect sizes, confidence intervals); and (d) low risk of small-study bias. The remaining five units (ASU: $k$=7, MPU: $k$=21, NDU: $k$=3, PCU: $k$=6, RPU: $k$=6) are included in the framework with descriptive statistics, providing preliminary evidence for future meta-analyses as literature expands. The complete study selection process is illustrated in Figure~\ref{fig:prisma}.

\vspace{-0.2em}
\textbf{Effect Size Interpretation Guidelines.} Following \citet{borenstein2021} conventions: $d < 0.5$ = small, $0.5 \leq d < 0.8$ = medium, $d \geq 0.8$ = large. Core-4 units demonstrate medium-to-large effects: \STU{} ($d=0.67$, medium), \IMU{} ($d=0.53$, medium), \SPU{} ($d=0.84$, large), \ARU{} ($d=0.83$, large). These magnitudes exceed typical cognitive neuroscience meta-analytic effects ($\bar{d} \approx 0.40$; \citealt{hedges1998}), indicating robust and replicable music-brain relationships with meaningful practical significance.

