\subsection{Moderator Analysis: Sample Size Effects}

After strict quality filtering (Cohen's $d$ only, $|d| < 2$), \Isquared{} values ranged from 61.8\% (\ARU{}) to 95.8\% (\IMU{}). The moderate heterogeneity for \ARU{} reflects relatively consistent affective responses, while higher values for other units reflect methodological diversity (fMRI vs EEG vs behavioral paradigms, musicians vs non-musicians). We conducted planned moderator analyses to identify sources of variance. Sample size emerged as a significant moderator of effect sizes (Table~\ref{tab:moderator}).

\textbf{Multiple Comparisons.} We conducted multiple meta-analyses (4 Core-4 units) and multiple moderator analyses (sample size, modality, musical training, paradigm). \textbf{Note:} We did not apply multiple comparisons correction (e.g., Bonferroni, FDR) for the following reasons: (1) Meta-analytic pooling uses random-effects models that account for between-study variance, reducing false positive rates compared to individual study analyses; (2) Our primary analyses (pooled effect sizes) are confirmatory and hypothesis-driven (testing whether each unit shows significant effects), not exploratory data mining; (3) Moderator analyses are exploratory and reported with appropriate caution; (4) All pooled effect sizes remain significant even under conservative Bonferroni correction ($\alpha = 0.05/4 = 0.0125$ for Core-4 units, all $p < .001$). However, readers should interpret moderator analysis results (particularly subgroup comparisons) with awareness of multiple testing, and we report uncorrected $p$-values with explicit acknowledgment of this limitation.

\textbf{Descriptive Statistics vs. Meta-Analysis for Small-$k$ Units.} Five units (ASU: $k$=7, MPU: $k$=21, NDU: $k$=3, PCU: $k$=6, RPU: $k$=6) had insufficient sample sizes for reliable meta-analysis ($k < 10$ recommended minimum; \citealt{borenstein2021}). For these units, we report \textbf{descriptive statistics} (mean effect sizes, ranges) rather than pooled meta-analytic estimates. \textbf{Important distinction:} (1) \textbf{Meta-analysis} (Core-4 units): Random-effects models with confidence intervals, prediction intervals, heterogeneity statistics, and publication bias assessment; (2) \textbf{Descriptive statistics} (small-$k$ units): Simple means and ranges without inferential statistics, as these would be unreliable with $k < 10$. We explicitly label these as ``mean effect size'' in tables to avoid confusion. Future work should expand literature searches for these units to enable proper meta-analysis.

