\subsection{Unit-Specific Findings}

This section provides concise summaries for each core unit, including neural substrates, meta-analytic effect sizes, and key theoretical models. Detailed mechanistic descriptions of Tier $\alpha$, $\beta$, and $\gamma$ models are presented in Section~\ref{sec:detailed-models} (Detailed Theoretical Models).

\subsubsection{Spectral Processing Unit (\SPU{})}

The \SPU{} encompasses a hierarchically organized network extending from peripheral auditory structures through primary and association auditory cortices. Key nodes identified across 46 studies include:

\textbf{Subcortical Pathway:} The cochlea, auditory nerve ($n$=5 mentions), inferior colliculus ($n$=4), and auditory brainstem ($n$=8) constitute the ascending pathway for spectral feature extraction. Frequency following response (FFR) studies demonstrate that consonance hierarchies are established at the brainstem level, preceding cortical processing \citep{bidelman2013}.

\textbf{Primary Auditory Cortex:} Heschl's gyrus ($n$=6, including lateralized variants), A1 ($n$=3), and the primary auditory cortex ($n$=3) exhibit tonotopic organization and pitch-selective responses. Penagos and colleagues demonstrated lateral HG specialization for pitch salience using fMRI.

\textbf{Association Regions:} The superior temporal gyrus ($n$=9 including variants), supplementary motor area ($n$=7), and anterior cingulate cortex ($n$=7 including variants) are implicated in higher-order spectral integration.

\subsubsection{Effect Sizes}

Meta-analysis of 13 quality-filtered effect sizes from 46 papers (Cohen's $d$ only, $|d|<2$) yielded a pooled \cohend{0.84} [95\% CI: 0.44--1.24; 95\% PI: --0.73 to 2.41] for spectral processing contrasts. Heterogeneity was substantial (\Isquared{}=93.4\%, \tausquared{}=0.47), reflecting diverse paradigms across fMRI, EEG, and behavioral studies. The wide prediction interval indicates that future studies may show effects ranging from negative to large positive values. Figure~\ref{fig:forest_spu} presents the forest plot.

