\subsubsection{Key Theoretical Models}

\textbf{Tier $\alpha$ (High-Confidence Mechanisms):} Three mechanistic models with converging multi-study evidence: (1) \textbf{Brainstem Consonance Hierarchy (BCH):} Consonance perception reflects harmonicity-based neural pitch salience encoded at brainstem level (FFR magnitude correlates with behavioral consonance: $r=0.81$, $p<0.001$, $n=40$); (2) \textbf{Pitch Salience Cortical Localization (PSCL):} Pitch salience computation localized to anterolateral Heschl's gyrus with parametric increases as function of periodicity strength; (3) \textbf{Pitch Chroma Cortical Representation (PCCR):} Chroma (pitch class) representation in non-primary auditory cortex, independent of octave.

\textbf{Tier $\beta$ (Integrative Models):} Three integrative models: (1) \textbf{Spectral-Temporal Aesthetic Integration (STAI):} Aesthetic preference jointly determined by spectral complexity and temporal predictability; (2) \textbf{Timbre-Specific Cortical Plasticity (TSCP):} Musical training induces timbre-specific reorganization of auditory cortex; (3) \textbf{Musical Imagery Auditory Activation (MIAA):} Musical imagery activates auditory cortex in absence of physical sound.

\textbf{Tier $\gamma$ (Speculative Models):} Three speculative models requiring further validation: (1) \textbf{Stimulus-Dependent Neural Pitch Salience (SDNPS):} NPS predicts behavior for synthetic tones but not natural sounds; (2) \textbf{Expertise-Specific MMN Enhancement (ESME):} MMN amplitude reflects sound parameters most relevant to musician's expertise; (3) \textbf{Sensory Dissonance Early Detection (SDED):} Sensory dissonance detected at early stages regardless of musical expertise.

Detailed mechanistic descriptions, mathematical formulations, neural architecture diagrams, and white-box model construction details are presented in Section~\ref{sec:detailed-models}.

\subsection{Sensorimotor Timing Unit (\STU{})}

\subsubsection{Neural Substrates}

The \STU{} comprises a distributed network supporting temporal encoding, beat induction, and auditory-motor coupling across 104 studies:

\textbf{Auditory Temporal Regions:} The superior temporal gyrus ($n$=21) serves as the primary hub for temporal structure encoding. The STG exhibits sensitivity to beat structure, rhythmic complexity, and temporal predictions.

\textbf{Motor Network:} The supplementary motor area ($n$=15), primary motor cortex ($n$=7), and premotor regions ($n$=5+) show activation during passive music listening, suggesting automatic motor simulation of rhythmic structure.

\textbf{Memory-Timing Interface:} Hippocampus ($n$=9) and medial prefrontal cortex ($n$=8) contribute to temporal context encoding over extended timescales.

\textbf{Affect-Timing Interface:} Anterior cingulate cortex ($n$=7) and amygdala ($n$=6) modulate attentional allocation and emotional salience of temporal events.

\subsubsection{Effect Sizes}

Meta-analysis of 60 quality-filtered effect sizes from 104 papers (Cohen's $d$ only, $|d|<2$) yielded a pooled \cohend{0.67} [95\% CI: 0.52--0.82; 95\% PI: --0.38 to 1.72] for timing-related contrasts. Heterogeneity was substantial (\Isquared{}=86.7\%, \tausquared{}=0.27), consistent with diverse paradigms ranging from beat perception to sensorimotor synchronization. The prediction interval spans from negative to moderate positive effects, reflecting methodological diversity. Figure~\ref{fig:forest_stu} presents the forest plot.

