\subsubsection{Key Theoretical Models}

\textbf{Tier $\alpha$ (High-Confidence Mechanisms):} Three mechanistic models: (1) \textbf{Hierarchical Musical Context Encoding (HMCE):} Temporal context integration follows transformer-like hierarchical architecture in auditory cortex with context window expansion ($W(\text{layer}) = W_0 \cdot k^{\text{layer}}$); (2) \textbf{Auditory-Motor Stream Coupling (AMSC):} Beat perception automatically engages motor simulation circuits via STG--SMA connectivity; (3) \textbf{Melody Decoding from Neural Signals (MDNS):} Melodic structure can be decoded from neural activity patterns using machine learning approaches.

\textbf{Tier $\beta$ (Integrative Models):} Integrative models linking timing with other cognitive domains (memory, attention, prediction).

\textbf{Tier $\gamma$ (Speculative Models):} Speculative models requiring further validation.

Detailed mechanistic descriptions, mathematical formulations, and neural architecture diagrams are presented in Section~\ref{sec:detailed-models}.

\subsection{Integrative Memory Unit (\IMU{})}

\subsubsection{Neural Substrates}

The \IMU{} exhibits the largest evidence base (213 studies) and encompasses memory systems from encoding through long-term consolidation:

\textbf{Hippocampal System:} The hippocampus ($n$=88) represents the most frequently cited region, reflecting its central role in binding musical elements with autobiographical context. Hippocampal activation increases for familiar versus novel music and for personally meaningful selections.

\textbf{Motor Memory:} The supplementary motor area ($n$=67) and primary motor cortex ($n$=21) contribute to procedural musical memory, including performance skills and implicit rhythm learning.

\textbf{Auditory Processing:} Superior temporal gyrus ($n$=26), auditory cortex ($n$=21), A1 ($n$=18), and Heschl's gyrus ($n$=8) support perceptual encoding of musical features that form the basis for memory traces.

\textbf{Executive and Self-Referential:} Anterior cingulate cortex ($n$=17), medial prefrontal cortex ($n$=14), and the default mode network ($n$=8) are implicated in self-referential processing and evaluation of personal significance.

\textbf{Emotional Binding:} Amygdala ($n$=12) and emotional processing regions contribute to the affective tagging of musical memories.

\subsubsection{Effect Sizes}

Random-effects meta-analysis of 60 quality-filtered effect sizes from 213 papers (Cohen's $d$ only, $|d|<2$) yielded a pooled \cohend{0.53} [95\% CI: 0.42--0.65; 95\% PI: --0.25 to 1.31] for memory-related contrasts. Heterogeneity was substantial (\Isquared{}=95.8\%, \tausquared{}=0.15), reflecting diverse memory paradigms (recognition, recall, familiarity). The wide prediction interval (spanning negative to moderate positive effects) indicates high variability across future studies. Figure~\ref{fig:forest_imu} presents the forest plot.

