\subsubsection{Key Theoretical Models}

\textbf{Tier $\alpha$ (High-Confidence Mechanisms):} Three mechanistic models: (1) \textbf{Music-Evoked Autobiographical Memory Network (MEAMN):} Familiar music triggers autobiographical recall through hippocampal-prefrontal network, preserved even in advanced dementia; (2) \textbf{Pythagorean Neural Hierarchy (PNH):} Musical intervals encoded in hierarchical neural representation following mathematical relationships; (3) \textbf{Musical Mnemonic Preservation (MMP):} Musical memories show enhanced preservation compared to verbal memories, with distinct neural encoding.

\textbf{Tier $\beta$ (Integrative Models):} Integrative models linking memory with other cognitive domains (emotion, attention, temporal processing).

\textbf{Tier $\gamma$ (Speculative Models):} Speculative models requiring further validation.

Detailed mechanistic descriptions, mathematical formulations, and neural architecture diagrams are presented in Section~\ref{sec:detailed-models}.

\subsection{Affective Resonance Unit (\ARU{})}

\subsubsection{Neural Substrates}

The \ARU{} encompasses the smallest but most effect-rich evidence base (42 studies, 87 claims), focusing on emotional and reward processing:

\textbf{Motor-Affective Interface:} Supplementary motor area ($n$=11) and superior temporal gyrus ($n$=7) link perceptual processing with affective responses.

\textbf{Reward System:} Nucleus accumbens ($n$=5), ventral striatum ($n$=4), caudate ($n$=4), and putamen ($n$=3) constitute the dopaminergic reward pathway activated during musical pleasure.

\textbf{Emotional Processing:} Amygdala ($n$=4), insula ($n$=4), and hippocampus ($n$=5) support rapid affective evaluation and emotional memory formation.

\textbf{Cognitive-Affective Integration:} Inferior frontal gyrus ($n$=4) and anterior cingulate cortex ($n$=3) mediate interactions between cognitive appraisal and emotional response.

\subsubsection{Effect Sizes}

Meta-analysis of 16 quality-filtered effect sizes from 42 papers (Cohen's $d$ only, $|d|<2$) yielded a pooled \cohend{0.83} [95\% CI: 0.61--1.05; 95\% PI: 0.05 to 1.61] for affective contrasts. Notably, heterogeneity was moderate (\Isquared{}=61.8\%, \tausquared{}=0.12), indicating relatively consistent affective responses to music across studies. The narrower prediction interval (compared to other units) reflects lower heterogeneity. Figure~\ref{fig:forest_aru} presents the forest plot.

Effect sizes ranged from $d$=0.05 to $d$=2.0, with a median of 0.84.

