\subsubsection{Key Theoretical Models}

\textbf{Tier $\alpha$ (High-Confidence Mechanisms):} Three mechanistic models: (1) \textbf{Striatal Reward Pathway (SRP):} Consonant music triggers dopaminergic release in nucleus accumbens and ventral tegmental area, generating pleasure responses; (2) \textbf{Autonomic-Affective Coupling (AAC):} Musical emotion modulates autonomic nervous system responses (heart rate, skin conductance) through brainstem and insular pathways; (3) \textbf{Valence-Mode Mapping (VMM):} Musical mode (major/minor) systematically modulates emotional valence through cortical-subcortical interactions.

\textbf{Tier $\beta$ (Integrative Models):} Integrative models linking affective processing with other cognitive domains (memory, attention, prediction).

\textbf{Tier $\gamma$ (Speculative Models):} Speculative models requiring further validation.

Detailed mechanistic descriptions, mathematical formulations, and neural architecture diagrams are presented in Section~\ref{sec:detailed-models}.

\subsubsection{Pathway 1: Consonance $\rightarrow$ Pleasure (\SPU{} $\rightarrow$ \ARU{})}

Spectral consonance processed by brainstem and auditory cortical mechanisms (\SPU{}) generates reduced prediction error, triggering dopaminergic reward responses in the striatum (\ARU{}):

\begin{center}
\small
\textbf{SPU.BCH} $\rightarrow$ Reduced PE $\rightarrow$ NAcc DA $\rightarrow$ Pleasure
\end{center}

Evidence: $k$=7 studies, \correlation{0.81} (SPU consonance $\leftrightarrow$ behavioral ratings),  \correlation{0.84} (NAcc DA $\leftrightarrow$ pleasure). Confidence: Very High ($\alpha$--$\alpha$ pathway).

\subsubsection{Pathway 2: Beat $\rightarrow$ Motor Synchronization (\STU{})}

Rhythmic input processed by posterior STG generates predictive signals to premotor cortex, enabling anticipatory motor planning:

\begin{center}
\small
\textbf{STU.AMSC}: pSTG $\xrightarrow{110\text{ms}}$ Premotor $\rightarrow$ Motor $\rightarrow$ Movement
\end{center}

Evidence: $k$=12 studies, \correlation{0.70} (auditory-motor coupling). Confidence: Very High ($\alpha$ tier).

\subsubsection{Pathway 3: Music $\rightarrow$ Autobiographical Memory (\IMU{} $\rightarrow$ \ARU{})}

Familiar music activates hippocampal memory systems, triggering autobiographical recall that is subsequently emotionally tagged by amygdala:

\begin{center}
\small
\textbf{IMU.MEAMN} $\rightarrow$ Hippocampus $\rightarrow$ Recall $\rightarrow$ Amygdala $\rightarrow$ Emotion
\end{center}

Evidence: $k$=4 studies, multiple modalities. Preserved in Alzheimer's disease. Confidence: High ($\alpha$--$\alpha$ pathway).

\subsubsection{Pathway 4: Temporal Hierarchy $\rightarrow$ Prediction (\STU{})}

Hierarchical temporal encoding in auditory cortex integrates context over progressively longer timescales, enabling prediction of upcoming musical events:

\begin{center}
\small
\textbf{STU.HMCE}: A1 $\rightarrow$ STG $\rightarrow$ MTG $\rightarrow$ TP $\rightarrow$ Prediction
\end{center}

Evidence: \correlation{0.99} (electrode distance--context), iEEG ($n$=29). Expertise effect: 3$\times$ context in musicians. Confidence: Very High ($\alpha$ tier).

\subsubsection{Pathway 5: Tempo $\rightarrow$ Emotion (\STU{} $\rightarrow$ \ARU{})}

Tempo encoding in motor-auditory circuits generates arousal modulation:

\begin{center}
\small
Fast tempo $\rightarrow$ $\uparrow$Beta/Gamma $\rightarrow$ $\uparrow$Arousal $\rightarrow$ Positive Valence
\end{center}

Evidence: L6.tempo\_bpm mentions: \STU{} (83), \ARU{} (23). EEG power modulation confirmed. Confidence: Moderate--High.

