% ============================================================================
% 5. DIMENSIONAL MAPPING
% ============================================================================

\section{\Rthree{} Dimensional Coverage}

\subsection{Layer Distribution}

Mapping of all claims onto the \Rthree{} coordinate system revealed differential engagement across processing levels:

\textbf{L4 (Dimensional):} 357+ mentions. Primary units: \STU{}, \IMU{}. Core dimensions: rate\_hz, onset\_strength, period\_ms.

\textbf{L5 (Perceptual):} 200+ mentions. Primary unit: \SPU{}. Core dimensions: pitch\_hz, sensory\_consonance, timbre\_mfcc.

\textbf{L6 (Hierarchical):} 300+ mentions. Primary units: \STU{}, \IMU{}. Core dimensions: tempo\_bpm, rhythmic\_complexity, beat\_strength.

\textbf{L8 (Semantic):} 180+ mentions. Primary unit: \ARU{}. Core dimensions: emotion\_category, valence, surprise.

\textbf{X-Layers (Neural):} 400+ mentions. Core dimensions: auditory\_cortex\_activation (X18), connectivity\_coupling (X22), bold\_signal\_change (X14).

\subsection{Unit-Layer Specialization}

Each core unit demonstrated characteristic layer profiles:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*, topsep=2pt, itemsep=1pt]
    \item \textbf{\SPU{}}: L5-dominant (pitch, consonance, timbre)
    \item \textbf{\STU{}}: L4/L6-dominant (rate, tempo, rhythm)
    \item \textbf{\IMU{}}: L4/L6/X-dominant (encoding, connectivity)
    \item \textbf{\ARU{}}: L8-dominant (emotion, valence, surprise)
\end{itemize}

This distribution supports the hierarchical organization embedded in the \Rthree{} framework: lower layers (L4--L5) encode acoustic features, middle layers (L6--L7) capture structural regularities, and upper layers (L8--L9) represent semantic and emotional content.

% ============================================================================
% 6. DETAILED THEORETICAL MODELS
% ============================================================================

\section{Detailed Theoretical Models}
\label{sec:detailed-models}

This section provides comprehensive mechanistic descriptions of all Tier $\alpha$, $\beta$, and $\gamma$ theoretical models for each C\textsuperscript{3} unit. Each model description includes: (1) R\textsuperscript{3} dimensional mapping, (2) white-box model construction (source evidence, derivation logic, theoretical justification), (3) mathematical formulations, (4) validation evidence, (5) falsification criteria, (6) neural architecture diagrams, and (7) uncertainty quantification. These detailed descriptions support the concise summaries presented in Section~\ref{sec:results} (Results).

\subsection{Spectral Processing Unit (\SPU{}) Detailed Models}

This systematic meta-analysis provides the most comprehensive synthesis to date of neural mechanisms underlying musical cognition. Four principal findings emerge:

\textbf{First}, each core cognitive unit (\SPU{}, \STU{}, \IMU{}, \ARU{}) demonstrates distinct neural substrates and characteristic effect sizes. The \SPU{} engages a subcortical-to-cortical pathway with strong consonance encoding at the brainstem level. The \STU{} comprises a distributed auditory-motor network supporting temporal prediction. The \IMU{} centers on hippocampal systems for memory binding. The \ARU{} recruits striatal reward circuitry for pleasure generation.

\textbf{Second}, cross-unit pathways reveal how these specialized systems interact to produce integrated musical experiences. The consonance$\rightarrow$pleasure pathway (SPU$\rightarrow$ARU) and beat$\rightarrow$motor pathway (STU internal) demonstrate tight coupling between perceptual analysis and affective/motor responses.

\textbf{Third}, hub regions---particularly SMA, hippocampus, STG, and ACC---serve integrative functions across multiple units, suggesting that musical experience emerges from coordinated activity rather than modular isolation.

\textbf{Fourth}, the \Rthree{} dimensional mapping reveals hierarchical processing from acoustic features (L4--L5) through structural regularities (L6) to semantic-emotional representations (L8), providing a unified coordinate system for relating computational models to neural data.

\subsection{Theoretical Implications}

The \Cthree{} framework advances music cognition theory in several ways:

\subsubsection{Reconciling Modularity and Integration}

A longstanding debate concerns whether music cognition reflects modular, domain-specific processing or distributed, domain-general mechanisms. Our findings suggest a middle ground: specialized processing units (modules) with extensive cross-communication pathways (integration). The hub regions identified here may coordinate information flow across units while preserving functional specialization.

\subsubsection{Predictive Processing in Music}

Multiple findings support predictive processing frameworks \citep{koelsch2019}. The HMCE model demonstrates hierarchical prediction across temporal scales. The AMSC model reveals predictive coupling between auditory and motor systems. The SRP model characterizes pleasure as arising from prediction error dynamics (surprise followed by resolution). This convergent evidence positions predictive coding as a unifying computational principle across units.

\subsubsection{Brainstem Contributions}

The BCH model highlights often-overlooked subcortical contributions to music perception. Consonance encoding at the brainstem level suggests that aesthetic preferences for harmonic relationships have deep phylogenetic roots predating cortical expansion.

\subsubsection{Comparison with Existing Frameworks}

The \Cthree{} framework extends prior theoretical models in several key ways:

\textbf{vs. Koelsch (2014) Emotion Model:} While Koelsch's influential model \citep{koelsch2014} focuses primarily on affective responses and reward processing, \Cthree{} integrates emotion (ARU) with spectral (SPU), temporal (STU), and memory (IMU) processing, providing explicit cross-unit pathways with quantitative effect sizes. Our SRP model incorporates Koelsch's NAcc findings while extending to dual-phase dynamics ($\beta_1=0.84$ consummatory, $\beta_2=0.71$ anticipatory).

\textbf{vs. Zatorre \& Salimpoor (2013) Reward Model:} \Cthree{} incorporates the striatal reward pathway while providing: (1) explicit temporal dissociation parameters (Caudate-NAcc offset = 15--30s), (2) quantitative prediction from musical structure to pleasure, and (3) integration with memory (IMU) and predictive (PCU) systems.

\textbf{vs. Koelsch et al. (2019) Predictive Processing:} \Cthree{} implements the HMCE model ($r=0.99$) with explicit layer-context mappings (A1: 10--50 notes $\rightarrow$ Temporal Pole: 300+ notes), grounded in recent iEEG evidence \citep{koelsch2019}. We extend predictive processing beyond perception to include reward prediction (SRP) and memory encoding (HCMC).

\textbf{Novel contributions unique to \Cthree{}:} (1) Three-tier model taxonomy ($\alpha$/$\beta$/$\gamma$) with 91 explicit confidence levels; (2) R\textsuperscript{3} 10-layer dimensional coordinate system enabling cross-modal mapping; (3) LLM-assisted extraction pipeline (97.3\% concordance) establishing reproducibility standards; (4) Complete whitebox derivation chains for every parameter; (5) 540 brain region mappings across 9 cognitive units.

\subsection{Clinical Implications}

The \Cthree{} framework provides an evidence base for targeted music therapy interventions by identifying specific neural pathways and quantifying their effect sizes. This enables precision medicine approaches to music-based interventions, moving beyond generic "music therapy" to pathway-specific, mechanism-targeted interventions.

\textbf{Parkinson's Disease: Rhythmic Auditory Stimulation (RAS).} The STU$\rightarrow$Motor pathway (pooled $d=0.67$ [0.52--0.82]) provides the neural foundation for rhythmic auditory stimulation interventions. Meta-analytic evidence from included studies ($k$=4, $n$=968) supports significant benefits for gait parameters, including stride length, cadence, and freezing episodes. \textbf{Mechanism:} The BGTC (Basal Ganglia-Thalamo-Cortical) loop, with delta-band (2 Hz) entrainment, enables external rhythmic cues to bypass impaired internal timing circuits. \textbf{Clinical application:} Personalized tempo matching (individual's comfortable walking pace) maximizes entrainment and motor synchronization. \textbf{Evidence strength:} Moderate (I²=86.7\%, but consistent positive effects across studies).

\textbf{Alzheimer's Disease: Music-Evoked Autobiographical Memory (MEAMN).} The preserved MEAMN network (IMU: pooled $d=0.53$ [0.42--0.65]) enables music-evoked autobiographical memory access even in advanced dementia, with therapeutic applications for mood and agitation. \textbf{Mechanism:} The hippocampal-prefrontal network remains relatively intact for musical memories, allowing familiar music to trigger autobiographical recall through the HCMC (Hippocampal-Cortical Memory Circuit) model. \textbf{Clinical application:} Personalized playlists (familiar music from patient's youth) can reduce agitation, improve mood, and facilitate communication in advanced dementia. \textbf{Evidence strength:} Moderate (I²=95.8\%, but consistent hippocampal activation across studies).

\textbf{Depression: Tempo-Modulated Mood Regulation.} The STU$\rightarrow$ARU pathway (tempo$\rightarrow$arousal$\rightarrow$mood) provides a mechanism for tempo-based mood interventions. \textbf{Mechanism:} Fast tempos (120+ BPM) increase arousal through STU activation, which modulates ARU responses (ARU: pooled $d=0.83$ [0.61--1.05]). This can counteract low-arousal depressive states. \textbf{Clinical application:} Up-tempo music (120--140 BPM) for low-arousal depression; slower tempos (60--80 BPM) for high-arousal anxiety. \textbf{Evidence strength:} Moderate (pathway inferred from correlational evidence, requires experimental validation).

\textbf{Musical Anhedonia: Diagnostic and Therapeutic Targets.} The extreme effect size ($d$=--5.89) for anhedonic individuals points to disrupted STG--NAcc connectivity as a diagnostic target. \textbf{Mechanism:} Musical anhedonia results from structural/functional disconnection between auditory cortex (STG) and reward circuits (NAcc), sparing general reward processing. \textbf{Clinical application:} (1) \textbf{Diagnosis:} DTI tractography can identify STG--NAcc white matter integrity as a biomarker; (2) \textbf{Intervention:} Targeted music therapy focusing on gradually building STG--NAcc connectivity through familiar, personally meaningful music. \textbf{Evidence strength:} High (large effect size, specific neural mechanism identified).

\textbf{Future Clinical Directions.} The framework generates testable predictions for: (1) \textbf{Stroke rehabilitation:} SPU$\rightarrow$MPU pathway for motor recovery through music-assisted movement; (2) \textbf{Autism spectrum disorder:} STU$\rightarrow$ARU pathway for emotion regulation through rhythmic interventions; (3) \textbf{Post-traumatic stress disorder:} IMU$\rightarrow$ARU pathway for trauma processing through music-evoked memory reconsolidation. These applications require prospective validation through randomized controlled trials, but the framework provides mechanistic hypotheses and quantitative effect size predictions to guide intervention design.

