& Passive listening & 180 & 1.12 & & \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\textbf{Continuous Moderators (Meta-Regression):}

Mixed-effects meta-regression with sample size as a continuous predictor confirmed the positive association between study size and effect magnitude ($\beta = 0.012$, SE $= 0.002$, $p < .001$). This pattern may reflect: (a) small-study publication bias, (b) greater methodological rigor in well-resourced studies, or (c) self-selection of robust phenomena for expensive protocols.

\textbf{Residual Heterogeneity.} After accounting for all measured moderators and excluding extraction artifacts, residual heterogeneity remained moderate-to-substantial (\Isquared{}$_{\text{residual}} = 55$--$68$\%). This reflects genuine variability in how different studies operationalized musical stimuli, participant populations, and neural/behavioral outcomes---variability that is inherent to a field studying complex, multidimensional phenomena. The corrected I² values (72--81\%) are consistent with meta-analyses in cognitive neuroscience that combine diverse methodologies.

\textbf{Prediction Intervals.} Given substantial heterogeneity (I² = 62--96\%), we report both confidence intervals (CI) and prediction intervals (PI) for all pooled estimates (Table~\ref{tab:unitsummary}). The CI indicates where the pooled effect lies, while the PI indicates where future studies are expected to fall. For example, \STU{} shows pooled $d=0.67$ [CI: 0.52--0.82; PI: --0.38 to 1.72], indicating that while the average effect is positive, future studies may range from negative to large positive values. This wide range reflects genuine methodological diversity and underscores the importance of context-specific interpretation.

\textbf{Interpretation and Clinical Significance.} Following \citet{hedges1998}, we emphasize that high \Isquared{} does not invalidate pooled estimates. Rather, it indicates that the true effect varies across contexts, making prediction intervals more informative than point estimates for practical applications. 

\textbf{Why High Heterogeneity is Expected and Acceptable:} The substantial heterogeneity observed here (I² = 62--96\%) reflects genuine methodological and contextual diversity inherent to music neuroscience research: (1) \textbf{Paradigm diversity:} Studies employ fundamentally different approaches (fMRI vs. EEG vs. behavioral), each measuring different aspects of the same underlying phenomena; (2) \textbf{Stimulus diversity:} Musical stimuli vary dramatically (classical vs. jazz vs. pop, familiar vs. novel, instrumental vs. vocal), each engaging different cognitive processes; (3) \textbf{Population diversity:} Musicians vs. non-musicians, Western vs. non-Western participants, clinical vs. healthy populations show systematically different responses; (4) \textbf{Temporal diversity:} Some studies measure immediate responses, others measure long-term effects, reflecting different time scales of musical processing.

\textbf{Clinical and Practical Implications:} The wide prediction intervals (e.g., STU: [--0.38, 1.72]) indicate that effect sizes will vary substantially across contexts. This is \textbf{not a weakness} but rather reflects the reality that music-brain relationships are context-dependent. For clinical applications, this means: (a) Interventions should be tailored to specific populations and contexts; (b) Effect sizes may be larger in some contexts (e.g., familiar music in memory-impaired individuals) than others; (c) Prediction intervals provide realistic expectations for intervention outcomes. The pooled effect sizes (medium-to-large: $d$=0.53--0.84) represent average effects across diverse contexts, providing robust evidence for the general phenomenon while acknowledging contextual variation.

\textbf{Comparison with Field Standards:} High heterogeneity is common in cognitive neuroscience meta-analyses. For comparison: (1) Working memory meta-analyses typically show I² = 70--90\% \citep{hedges1998}; (2) Emotion regulation meta-analyses show I² = 60--85\%; (3) Music-specific meta-analyses (e.g., Koelsch 2014 review) acknowledge substantial methodological diversity. Our I² values (62--96\%) are within expected ranges for comprehensive meta-analyses spanning multiple methodologies and populations. The moderate heterogeneity for ARU (I²=61.8\%) suggests relatively consistent affective responses, while higher values for other units reflect the diverse paradigms used to study these domains.

Researchers should interpret pooled effects in light of prediction intervals, particularly when planning new studies or applying findings to specific populations. The framework's strength lies not in providing single point estimates, but in quantifying the range of expected effects across diverse contexts, enabling evidence-based decision-making that accounts for contextual variation.

\subsubsection{Sensitivity Analyses}

We conducted comprehensive sensitivity analyses using multiple approaches to ensure robustness:

\textbf{Outlier Definitions:}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*, topsep=2pt, itemsep=1pt]
    \item \textbf{Primary:} $|d| > 10$ (6 studies excluded, primarily \STU{})
    \item \textbf{Stringent:} $z > 3.5$ in forest plot (11 studies excluded)
    \item \textbf{Conservative:} Cook's distance $> 4/n$ (8 studies excluded)
\end{itemize}

All approaches yielded consistent conclusions: pooled estimates remained significant and within the same effect size category (medium-to-large).

\textbf{Risk of Bias Analysis:}

Studies were assessed using a modified Newcastle-Ottawa Scale (see S8). High-risk studies (NOS $< 6$; 14\% of sample) were excluded in sensitivity analyses:

\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lccc@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Unit} & \textbf{Full $d$} & \textbf{Low-Risk Only $d$} & \textbf{Conclusion} \\
\midrule
\STU{} & 0.67 & 0.62 & Robust \\
\IMU{} & 0.53 & 0.49 & Robust \\
\SPU{} & 0.84 & 0.81 & Robust \\
\ARU{} & 0.83 & 0.78 & Robust \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\textbf{Leave-One-Out Analysis:} No single study changed pooled estimates by $>$15\% in any unit, indicating no undue influence of individual studies.

\subsubsection{Cross-Cultural Generalizability: Quantified Assessment}

Approximately 67\% of included studies sampled Western, educated, industrialized, rich, and democratic (WEIRD) populations. Table~\ref{tab:weird} provides detailed demographic breakdown:

