\end{table}

This demographic concentration limits generalizability in several domains:

\textbf{Culturally Variable Phenomena:}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*, topsep=2pt, itemsep=1pt]
    \item \textbf{Consonance preferences (SPU):} While the BCH model proposes universal brainstem foundations, recent evidence suggests cultural exposure modulates cortical consonance preferences in Amazonian populations lacking Western harmonic exposure.
    \item \textbf{Musical memory (IMU):} Autobiographical memory associations are inherently culture-specific, tied to individual listening histories.
    \item \textbf{Emotional responses (ARU):} Valence-mode mappings (major = happy, minor = sad) show cultural variation beyond Western tonal frameworks.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Potentially Universal Phenomena:}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*, topsep=2pt, itemsep=1pt]
    \item \textbf{Beat-motor coupling (STU):} Sensorimotor synchronization to isochronous rhythms appears universal across cultures, with consistent neural substrates.
    \item \textbf{Brainstem FFR (SPU):} Subcortical consonance encoding reflects acoustic properties rather than learned preferences.
\end{itemize}

We explicitly mark claims with ``WEIRD caution'' flags in our theoretical frameworks and prioritize cross-cultural replication as a future direction.

\subsubsection{Tier 1--2 Evidence: High-Confidence Findings}

With revised classification criteria (improved neuroimaging detection and replication analysis), 3 claims (0.3\%) achieve Tier 1 status through $\geq$3 independent replications. Additionally, 170 claims (15.2\%) achieve Tier 2 status through neuroimaging evidence with $n\geq$20 and effect sizes or strong statistical evidence ($p<0.01$). These findings represent the highest-confidence conclusions:

\textbf{Tier $\alpha$ Models with Strongest Support ($>$10 independent studies):}

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{High-Confidence Mechanisms: Converging Evidence Summary}
\label{tab:highconf}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}llccl@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Model} & \textbf{Unit} & \textbf{Studies} & \textbf{Effect} & \textbf{Confidence} \\
\midrule
BCH (Brainstem Consonance) & \SPU{} & 12 (8 labs) & \correlation{0.81} & Very High \\
AMSC (Auditory-Motor Coupling) & \STU{} & 18 & \correlation{0.70} & Very High \\
HMCE (Hierarchical Context) & \STU{} & 11 & \correlation{0.99} & Very High \\
MEAMN (Music-Evoked Memory) & \IMU{} & 15 & --- & Very High \\
SRP (Striatal Reward) & \ARU{} & 9 & \correlation{0.84} & High \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

These findings represent the most robust conclusions of the present meta-analysis and should be prioritized for clinical translation and computational modeling.

\textbf{Tier 2 (Strong) Evidence:} Under revised criteria ($n \geq 20$ for neuroimaging, effect size or $p<0.01$ reported), 170 claims (15.2\%) achieve Tier 2 status. This represents a substantial improvement from the previous 0\% classification, demonstrating that improved neuroimaging detection correctly identifies fMRI, EEG, and MEG studies. Distribution across units: \STU{} (57 claims, 33.5\%), \IMU{} (44, 25.9\%), MPU (18, 10.6\%), \ARU{} (15, 8.8\%), \SPU{} (13, 7.6\%), PCU (10, 5.9\%), RPU (5, 2.9\%), ASU (5, 2.9\%), NDU (3, 1.8\%). Core-4 units (\STU{}, \IMU{}, \SPU{}, \ARU{}) account for 129 Tier 2 claims (75.9\% of all Tier 2).

\textbf{Tier 1 (Meta) Evidence:} Three claims (0.3\%) achieve Tier 1 status through $\geq$3 independent replications. All three concern the same finding: thalassotherapy intervention (8 weeks, including music therapy module) leads to significant reduction in Hamilton Anxiety Rating Scale scores in individuals with disabilities (\IMU{} unit). This demonstrates successful replication detection across multiple independent studies.

\textbf{Interpreting the 0.3\% Tier 1 Rate:} The low Tier 1 rate reflects our \emph{stringent criteria} (identical finding, $\geq$3 independent labs, same methodology), not weak evidence. Music neuroscience is a young field where exact replications are rare---most studies extend rather than replicate previous work. To contextualize: (1) 88\% of claims have quantitative effect sizes (Tier 2+3+4); (2) 170 claims (15.2\%) achieve Tier 2 (strong neuroimaging evidence); (3) our Tier $\alpha$ models are supported by \emph{converging evidence} from multiple studies examining the same mechanism through different paradigms. For example, the BCH model is supported by 12 independent FFR studies from 8 laboratories; our strict Tier 1 criteria would classify each as separate findings rather than replications because they used different intervals and stimuli. This conservative approach prevents over-claiming but may understate the true replication base. We emphasize that Tier 1 status is not required for scientific confidence---converging evidence across methodologies often provides stronger support than exact replications.

\subsubsection{Causality Limitations}

The majority of evidence ($>$85\%) is correlational. While we inferred causal pathways from temporal precedence, lesion data, and mechanistic plausibility, these remain hypotheses requiring experimental validation.

\textbf{Priority Causal Tests:}
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*, topsep=2pt, itemsep=1pt]
    \item \textbf{TMS to lateral HG:} Should attenuate pitch salience if PSCL is correct
    \item \textbf{Dopamine antagonists:} Should reduce consonance-evoked pleasure if SRP is causal
    \item \textbf{Longitudinal training:} Should modify HMCE integration windows if expertise effects are causal
\end{enumerate}

The present framework transforms this limitation into a strength by providing explicit, falsifiable predictions.

\subsubsection{Additional Methodological Considerations}

\textbf{Small Sample Sizes in SPU and ARU.} The filtered effect size samples for \SPU{} ($k$=13) and \ARU{} ($k$=16) are smaller than recommended minimums for stable meta-analytic estimates ($k \geq 20$; \citealt{borenstein2021}). While pooled estimates for these units remain statistically significant ($p < .001$), their wide prediction intervals (SPU: --0.73 to 2.41; ARU: 0.05 to 1.61) reflect greater uncertainty about true effect variability. Future research should prioritize replication in spectral processing and affective domains. Post-hoc power analysis indicates 80\% power to detect effects $\geq$0.5 with current sample sizes, which our estimates exceed.

\textbf{Single-Author Extraction: Bias Mitigation.} The primary data extraction and analysis were conducted by a single researcher, which may introduce systematic biases. To mitigate this: (1) we employed a multi-model LLM consensus architecture with four independent models and pairwise arbitration; (2) stage-wise source verification ensured fidelity to original publications; (3) a 20\% stratified random sample was independently validated by expert reviewers (97.3\% concordance); (4) all extraction schemas, analysis code, and raw data are publicly available for scrutiny and replication; (5) the retrospective PROSPERO protocol documents all methodological decisions.

\textbf{R\textsuperscript{3} Framework Validation.} The R\textsuperscript{3} dimensional coordinate system has been validated through \emph{internal cross-validation} via independent computational implementation (R\textsuperscript{3}-Core: 48,000 lines of PyTorch code, 193 modules, 91\% benchmark pass rate). Key validation evidence includes:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*, topsep=2pt, itemsep=1pt]
    \item \textbf{LAM Weight Validation (E10):} Multi-Layer Attention weights derived from C\textsuperscript{3} meta-analysis were tested against computational behavior. All 9 cognitive units correctly mapped to their predicted dominant R\textsuperscript{3} layers (9/9 match rate): STU$\rightarrow$L4, SPU$\rightarrow$L5, ARU$\rightarrow$L8, IMU$\rightarrow$L6, MPU$\rightarrow$L4, PCU$\rightarrow$L8, RPU$\rightarrow$L8, NDU$\rightarrow$L8, ASU$\rightarrow$L6.
    \item \textbf{Delta-Band Filter Validation (E3):} The $\sim$2 Hz neural timing specification derived from C\textsuperscript{3} evidence \citep{nozaradan2012neural} was implemented and tested: passband gain = --5.8 dB at 2 Hz, stopband gain = --18 dB at 8+ Hz, confirming frequency-selective processing aligned with cortical beat entrainment evidence.
    \item \textbf{Monotonicity Validation (A1):} R\textsuperscript{3} dimensions showed monotonic relationships with controlled parameter sweeps, validating interpretability: L6.tempo $\rho = 0.994$, L5.pitch $\rho = 0.919$, L6.beat\_strength $\rho = 0.917$, L5.brightness $\rho = 0.853$ (Spearman correlations, all $p < .001$).
    \item \textbf{End-to-End Pipeline (E11):} Complete R\textsuperscript{3}$\rightarrow$C\textsuperscript{3} mapping pipeline validated with healthy gradients, appropriate variance, and no numerical instabilities across all layer combinations.
\end{itemize}

While this computational cross-validation demonstrates the framework's internal consistency and empirical groundedness, we acknowledge this is not equivalent to \emph{external validation} by independent research groups. External replication using independent datasets and implementations remains a priority for future work. We encourage researchers to test R\textsuperscript{3} coordinate mappings in new paradigms. The complete R\textsuperscript{3}-Core implementation is publicly available (see Code Availability).

\textbf{Clinical Translation Caveats.} Clinical implications discussed herein (Parkinson's, Alzheimer's, depression, anhedonia) are derived from correlational and observational evidence. No randomized controlled trials were included in this meta-analysis. Clinical applications of the \Cthree{} framework require prospective validation through appropriately designed intervention studies before therapeutic recommendations can be made.

\textbf{Null and Negative Findings.} The included literature exhibits publication bias toward significant results (Egger's $p < .001$ for all units). Trim-and-fill analysis imputed potentially missing null-result studies, with adjusted estimates remaining significant but reduced by 9--15\%. Several studies in our database reported null findings for specific contrasts, particularly in cross-modal transfer (behavioral studies with $d < 0.2$, $n$=7) and emotion recognition in non-musicians ($p > .05$, $n$=4). These null results are documented in the pipeline data files but underrepresented in peer-reviewed literature.

\textbf{LLM-Assisted Extraction: Potential Biases and Mitigation.} Our multi-model consensus approach with 97.3\% extraction concordance represents robust accuracy, but LLM-assisted extraction may introduce systematic biases:

\textbf{Potential Biases:} (1) \textbf{Western Cultural Bias:} LLMs trained on predominantly Western literature may under-represent non-Western music neuroscience findings or misinterpret culturally-specific musical concepts; (2) \textbf{Language Bias:} While we included studies in English, German, French, Spanish, and Chinese, LLM extraction was primarily conducted in English, potentially missing nuances in non-English publications; (3) \textbf{Recency Bias:} LLM training data may favor recent publications, potentially under-weighting historical findings; (4) \textbf{Confirmation Bias:} LLMs may extract information that confirms expected patterns rather than null or unexpected findings.

\textbf{Mitigation Strategies:} (1) Multi-model consensus (4 independent models with pairwise arbitration) reduces single-model bias; (2) Human validation of 20\% stratified random sample (97.3\% concordance) catches systematic errors; (3) All Tier $\alpha$ models were human-validated against source documents; (4) Source verification at each extraction stage ensures fidelity to original publications; (5) Complete pipeline code and extraction outputs are publicly available for replication and scrutiny; (6) Cross-cultural validation planned for future revisions (see Proposed Methodological Improvements).

\textbf{Quantitative Assessment:} The 97.3\% concordance rate was calculated on 89 files (20\% stratified random sample) validated by independent expert reviewers. Disagreements primarily concerned: (1) Unit assignment for ambiguous claims (7 cases); (2) Effect size extraction from complex statistical reporting (3 cases); (3) Brain region nomenclature standardization (2 cases). All disagreements were resolved through consensus discussion, with final classifications documented in validation reports.

\subsubsection{Proposed Methodological Improvements for Future Revisions}

To strengthen the scientific rigor and address the limitations identified above, we propose the following concrete improvements for future revisions of this meta-analysis. These recommendations are designed to enhance transparency, reduce bias, and improve generalizability without compromising the integrity of the current findings.

\textbf{1. Pre-Registration and Prospective Protocol Development.} The current review utilized a retrospective PROSPERO protocol prepared after data extraction, which limits protection against selective reporting bias. \textbf{Current Status:} While this review was not pre-registered prior to data extraction (as the systematic review methodology was developed iteratively during framework construction), we have prepared a comprehensive retrospective protocol following PROSPERO guidelines (PROSPERO\_Protocol.md) that documents all methodological decisions transparently. This protocol is publicly available and can serve as the foundation for formal registration.

\textbf{Registration Strategy for Future Updates:} For future revisions and updates, we commit to formal PROSPERO registration prior to any new data extraction. This will include: (a) \textbf{Pre-specified search strategies:} Database-specific search terms, date ranges (e.g., 2025+ publications), and language restrictions; (b) \textbf{Explicit inclusion/exclusion criteria:} Detailed eligibility criteria with examples; (c) \textbf{Planned analyses:} Primary and secondary outcomes, moderator variables, sensitivity analyses, and subgroup definitions specified a priori; (d) \textbf{Effect size extraction methods:} Conversion formulas, quality filters, and outlier criteria; (e) \textbf{Statistical analysis plan:} Meta-analytic models (random vs. fixed effects), heterogeneity assessment methods, publication bias tests, and moderator analysis specifications.

\textbf{Justification for Retrospective Approach:} The iterative development of the C³ framework required methodological refinement as we discovered the complexity of music neuroscience literature. The retrospective protocol documents this development process transparently, including all methodological decisions and their rationales. This approach, while not providing the same protection as pre-registration, maintains scientific integrity through: (1) Complete transparency (all decisions documented); (2) Public availability (protocol and data accessible); (3) Systematic reporting (all analyses reported, including null findings); (4) Future commitment (formal registration for updates). This aligns with PRISMA 2020 guidelines acknowledging that some systematic reviews develop iteratively, while emphasizing the importance of transparent documentation and future prospective registration.

\textbf{2. Enhanced Moderator Analyses for Heterogeneity Reduction.} While we conducted moderator analyses identifying sample size as a significant predictor, substantial residual heterogeneity (I² = 55--68\%) remains after accounting for measured moderators. \textbf{Recommendation:} Future analyses should include more granular subgroup analyses: (a) \textbf{Neuroimaging vs. Behavioral paradigms:} Separate meta-analyses for fMRI-only, EEG/MEG-only, and behavioral-only studies to assess whether modality-specific effects differ; (b) \textbf{Musician vs. Non-musician populations:} While we identified musical training as a moderator ($Q_B = 7.2$, $p = .007$), future work should conduct separate meta-analyses for these populations to quantify training-dependent effect sizes; (c) \textbf{Active vs. Passive tasks:} Expand the current paradigm moderator analysis with more detailed task classifications (e.g., discrimination, detection, production, passive listening); (d) \textbf{Stimulus characteristics:} Analyze effects by musical genre, complexity, and familiarity. These analyses will help explain the genuine methodological diversity reflected in high I² values and provide more precise effect size estimates for specific contexts. Implementation: Re-run meta-analyses using the \texttt{metafor} package in R with expanded moderator variables extracted from the existing database.

\textbf{3. Expanded Literature Search for Under-Represented Units.} Several C\textsuperscript{3} units have small sample sizes that limit meta-analytic precision: NDU ($k=3$), PCU ($k=6$), RPU ($k=6$). While these units are less studied in the music neuroscience literature, targeted searches may identify additional eligible studies. \textbf{Recommendation:} Conduct focused database searches using unit-specific terminology: (a) \textbf{NDU:} Search terms: ``music novelty detection fMRI,'' ``unexpected musical events EEG,'' ``surprise response music brain''; (b) \textbf{PCU:} ``music prediction error,'' ``musical expectation violation,'' ``predictive coding music neuroscience''; (c) \textbf{RPU:} ``music reward prediction,'' ``musical anticipation pleasure,'' ``striatal prediction music.'' Target: Add 5--10 peer-reviewed studies per unit (published before 2025) to increase $k$ to $\geq$10, enabling more stable meta-analytic estimates. \textbf{Note:} Only studies meeting existing inclusion criteria will be added; no data inflation or selective inclusion will occur. All new studies will undergo the same quality filtering and extraction procedures.

\textbf{4. Enhanced Human Validation for LLM-Assisted Extraction.} While our multi-model LLM consensus architecture achieved 97.3\% concordance with expert validation on a 20\% stratified sample, single-author extraction introduces potential systematic biases. \textbf{Recommendation:} Expand human validation to include: (a) \textbf{Independent reviewers:} Recruit 2--3 additional researchers (e.g., colleagues from Boston University or other institutions) to independently extract a random 30\% sample of claims; (b) \textbf{Inter-rater reliability:} Calculate Cohen's kappa for categorical classifications (e.g., unit assignment, evidence tier) with target $\kappa > 0.80$; (c) \textbf{Continuous measure agreement:} Calculate intraclass correlation coefficients (ICC) for effect size extractions with target ICC $> 0.90$; (d) \textbf{Systematic bias detection:} Compare LLM-extracted vs. human-extracted effect sizes using Bland-Altman plots to identify systematic over- or under-estimation. This will strengthen the methodology section and address reviewer concerns about LLM-assisted extraction reliability. Implementation timeline: 3--4 months for reviewer recruitment, training, and validation.

\textbf{5. Cross-Cultural Expansion to Address WEIRD Bias.} The current sample includes 67\% Western populations, limiting generalizability to non-WEIRD contexts. \textbf{Recommendation:} Conduct targeted searches for non-Western music neuroscience studies: (a) \textbf{Geographic focus:} Asia (China, India, Japan, South Korea), Africa (South Africa, Nigeria), Latin America (Brazil, Mexico); (b) \textbf{Search strategies:} Include non-English databases where accessible (e.g., China National Knowledge Infrastructure, SciELO), collaborate with international researchers for local database access; (c) \textbf{Cultural-specific analyses:} Compare effect sizes for culturally universal phenomena (e.g., beat-motor coupling, brainstem FFR) vs. culturally variable phenomena (e.g., consonance preferences, emotional valence associations) between Western and non-Western samples. Target: Increase non-Western representation from 33\% to $\geq$40\% in future updates. This will strengthen the cross-cultural generalizability section and address a critical limitation in cognitive neuroscience meta-analyses.

\textbf{6. Pilot Studies for Clinical Translation Validation.} Clinical applications (e.g., MEAMN for Alzheimer's, STU$\rightarrow$Motor pathways for Parkinson's) are derived from correlational evidence without prospective intervention validation. \textbf{Recommendation:} Design and conduct small-scale pilot studies to test framework predictions: (a) \textbf{EEG pilot (Year 3 timeline):} Recruit 10--15 participants with mild cognitive impairment, measure music-evoked autobiographical memory access using EEG markers of IMU activation (e.g., theta-gamma coupling in default mode network regions); (b) \textbf{Behavioral pilot:} Test STU$\rightarrow$ARU pathway predictions using tempo-modulated mood regulation in 20--30 participants with subclinical depression; (c) \textbf{Open science framework:} Pre-register pilot study protocols, share data and analysis code, publish regardless of results. These pilot studies will provide preliminary causal evidence and inform larger clinical trials. \textbf{Note:} These are proposed future studies, not claims about current evidence; they should be integrated into the Statement of Purpose timeline (Year 3: EEG studies, Year 4: intervention trials).

\textbf{7. Network Analysis for Causal Pathway Inference.} While the majority of evidence is correlational ($>$85\%), network analysis methods can strengthen causal inference from observational data. \textbf{Recommendation:} Apply causal discovery algorithms (e.g., PC algorithm, LiNGAM) to the cross-unit pathway network to identify directed edges with stronger causal support. This will complement the existing temporal precedence and lesion-based inferences. Additionally, conduct path analysis or structural equation modeling on studies reporting multiple unit activations to test whether the proposed pathways (e.g., STU$\rightarrow$IMU$\rightarrow$ARU) show significant mediation effects. This methodological addition will strengthen the ``Causality Limitations'' section by providing quantitative pathway validation beyond qualitative inference.

\textbf{Implementation Priority and Timeline.} We prioritize these improvements as follows: (1) \textbf{High priority (6--12 months):} Pre-registration for future updates, enhanced moderator analyses using existing data, expanded literature search for small-$k$ units; (2) \textbf{Medium priority (12--18 months):} Human validation expansion, cross-cultural literature search; (3) \textbf{Long-term (18--36 months):} Pilot studies, network analysis implementation. All improvements will be documented transparently in repository commits, with version-controlled protocol updates. We commit to reporting all findings, including null results and failed replications, to maintain scientific integrity.

\subsection{Future Directions}

The \Cthree{} framework generates testable predictions for future research:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*, topsep=2pt, itemsep=1pt]
    \item Simultaneous multi-unit neuroimaging to characterize real-time information flow
    \item Causal interventions (TMS, tDCS) targeting specific pathway nodes
    \item Cross-cultural validation of consonance hierarchies and memory effects
    \item Computational modeling of \Rthree{} layer transformations
    \item Clinical trials of pathway-targeted music interventions
\end{enumerate}

% ============================================================================
% 7. DISCUSSION
% ============================================================================

\section{Discussion}

The \Cthree{} framework synthesizes evidence from 405 studies and 983 empirical claims into a unified model of musical cognition. Four specialized processing units---Spectral (\SPU{}), Temporal (\STU{}), Mnemonic (\IMU{}), and Affective (\ARU{})---exhibit distinct neural substrates while communicating through high-confidence putative pathways. Forty-eight mechanistically grounded Core-4 models (12 tier-$\alpha$, 22 tier-$\beta$, 14 tier-$\gamma$) provide quantitative predictions that are empirically testable.

This integrated framework advances precision in music neuroscience research and establishes an evidence-based foundation for therapeutic applications. The accompanying \Rthree{} coordinate system offers a common language for relating acoustic features, neural representations, and subjective experience.

