\subsubsection{Tier $\beta$ Models: SPU Integrative Models}

\textbf{$\beta$.1 Spectral-Temporal Aesthetic Integration (STAI):}

Aesthetic preference for music is jointly determined by spectral complexity and temporal predictability, with optimal preference at intermediate levels of both dimensions. fMRI evidence shows reward-region activation peaks at moderate complexity (Kim fMRI: $n$=20).

\textbf{$\beta$.2 Timbre-Specific Cortical Plasticity (TSCP):}

Long-term musical training induces timbre-specific reorganization of auditory cortex, with enhanced representation of trained instrument timbres. MEG evidence demonstrates amplified N1m responses for trained vs. untrained instrument sounds (Pantev MEG: $n$=24).

\textbf{$\beta$.3 Musical Imagery Auditory Activation (MIAA):}

Musical imagery activates auditory cortex in the absence of physical sound, with activation patterns similar to perception. fMRI evidence shows bilateral STG/auditory cortex activation during imagined melodies (Kraemer fMRI: $n$=16).

\subsubsection{Tier $\gamma$ Models: SPU Speculative Models}

\textbf{$\gamma$.1 Stimulus-Dependent Neural Pitch Salience (SDNPS):}

Neural Pitch Salience (NPS) from brainstem FFR is not a universal consonance correlate; it predicts behavior for synthetic tones but not natural sounds.

\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}llcc@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Stimulus Type} & \textbf{NPS $\leftrightarrow$ Pleasantness} & \textbf{n} & \textbf{p} \\
\midrule
Synthetic Complex Tones & $r=0.34$ & 14 & $<$0.03 \\
Natural Sax & $r=0.24$ (n.s.) & 14 & n.s. \\
Natural Voice & $r=-0.10$ (n.s.) & 14 & n.s. \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\textbf{$\gamma$.2 Expertise-Specific MMN Enhancement (ESME):}

MMN amplitude reflects sound parameters most relevant to a musician's expertise, with training inducing feature-specific enhancement (Tervaniemi 2022: $d=-1.09$). Singers show enhanced pitch MMN; drummers show enhanced rhythm MMN; all musicians show enhanced timbre MMN for their trained instrument.

\textbf{$\gamma$.3 Sensory Dissonance Early Detection (SDED):}

Sensory dissonance (roughness) is detected at early sensory stages regardless of musical expertise, while musical expertise enhances behavioral but not neural discrimination. Musicians = non-musicians in MMN; musicians $>$ non-musicians in behavioral accuracy.

\subsection{Sensorimotor Timing Unit (\STU{})}

\subsubsection{Neural Substrates}

The \STU{} comprises a distributed network supporting temporal encoding, beat induction, and auditory-motor coupling across 104 studies:

\textbf{Auditory Temporal Regions:} The superior temporal gyrus ($n$=21) serves as the primary hub for temporal structure encoding. The STG exhibits sensitivity to beat structure, rhythmic complexity, and temporal predictions.

\textbf{Motor Network:} The supplementary motor area ($n$=15), primary motor cortex ($n$=7), and premotor regions ($n$=5+) show activation during passive music listening, suggesting automatic motor simulation of rhythmic structure.

\textbf{Memory-Timing Interface:} Hippocampus ($n$=9) and medial prefrontal cortex ($n$=8) contribute to temporal context encoding over extended timescales.

\textbf{Affect-Timing Interface:} Anterior cingulate cortex ($n$=7) and amygdala ($n$=6) modulate attentional allocation and emotional salience of temporal events.

\subsubsection{Effect Sizes}

Meta-analysis of 60 quality-filtered effect sizes (Cohen's $d$ only, $|d|<2$) yielded a pooled \cohend{0.67} [95\% CI: 0.52--0.82; 95\% PI: --0.38 to 1.72] for timing-related contrasts. Heterogeneity was substantial (\Isquared{}=86.7\%, \tausquared{}=0.27), consistent with diverse paradigms ranging from beat perception to sensorimotor synchronization. The prediction interval spans from negative to moderate positive effects, reflecting methodological diversity. Figure~\ref{fig:forest_stu} presents the forest plot.

