\subsubsection{Tier $\alpha$ Models: Hierarchical Musical Context Encoding (HMCE)}

\textbf{\Rthree{} Dimensional Mapping:}
\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{R³ Dimension} & \textbf{Role} & \textbf{Layer} \\
\midrule
L8.surprise & Prediction error & L8 (Semantic) \\
X18.auditory\_cortex\_activation & Neural response & X-layer (Neural) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

Recent intracranial EEG evidence provides exceptional support for the HMCE model, which proposes that temporal context integration follows a transformer-like hierarchical architecture in auditory cortex:

\begin{equation}
W(\text{layer}) = W_0 \cdot k^{\text{layer}}
\label{eq:context}
\end{equation}

where $W$ denotes context window size, $W_0$ is the base window ($\sim$50 ms at Layer 1), and $k$ is the expansion factor ($\sim$3--4$\times$ per layer).

\textbf{Key Evidence (Mischler 2025):}
\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lccc@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Finding} & \textbf{ES} & \textbf{n} & \textbf{p} \\
\midrule
Distance from pmHG $\leftrightarrow$ context encoding & \cohend{0.99} & 6 & $<$0.044 \\
Musicians $>$ non-musicians in layer 13 encoding & \cohend{0.32} & 20 & $<$3.8e-8 \\
Musicians integrate 300+ notes context & \cohend{0.32} & 20 & $<$0.05 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\textbf{Falsification Criteria:}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*, topsep=0pt, itemsep=0pt]
\item Lesions to temporal pole should impair long-range context processing
\item Non-musicians should show reduced late-layer encoding
\item Simple/repetitive music should not engage full hierarchy
\end{itemize}

