\subsubsection{Tier $\beta$ Models: STU Integrative Models}

\textbf{$\beta$.1 Attention-Modulated Stream Segregation (AMSS):}

Top-down attention modulates the segregation of competing auditory streams in complex musical contexts. EEG evidence shows distinct neural signatures for attended vs. unattended melodic streams during concurrent stimulation (Hausfeld EEG: $n$=24).

\textbf{$\beta$.2 Timbre Perception-Imagery Overlap (TPIO):}

Neural representations of perceived and imagined musical timbre overlap substantially in auditory association areas. fMRI evidence demonstrates timbre imagery activates similar regions as perception (behavioral\_timbre fMRI: $n$=16).

\textbf{$\beta$.3 Expertise-Dependent Tempo Accuracy (EDTA):}

Musicians show greater temporal precision than non-musicians in beat entrainment and tempo reproduction tasks, with training effects on sensorimotor timing circuits. Behavioral studies demonstrate graded improvements with musical training (Foster behavioral: $n$=30).

\textbf{$\beta$.4 Entrainment, Tempo \& Attention Modulation (ETAM):}

Neural oscillation synchronization to rhythmic stimuli modulates attention and tempo perception. The ETAM model proposes that entrainment at multiple temporal scales (beat, meter, phrase) creates attentional windows that enhance temporal processing. Key R³ dimensions: L6.tempo\_bpm (beat tracking), L4.rate\_hz (entrainment rate), X18.auditory\_cortex (oscillations). Brain regions: Motor Cortex, SMA, Cerebellum.

\textbf{$\beta$.5 Hierarchical Groove State Integration Circuit (HGSIC):}

Multi-level rhythmic pattern integration creates groove perception through hierarchical processing of beat, meter, and rhythmic complexity. The HGSIC model extends beat perception to include groove states that emerge from optimal complexity levels. Key R³ dimensions: L6.rhythmic\_complexity (groove), L6.beat\_strength (pulse), X18.motor\_cortex (movement). Brain regions: Basal Ganglia, SMA, Premotor.

\textbf{$\beta$.6 Oscillatory Motor Synchronization (OMS):}

Beta/gamma band motor-auditory coupling enables precise temporal synchronization between auditory rhythm and motor responses. The OMS model characterizes oscillatory entrainment in motor cortex that aligns with auditory beat structure. Key R³ dimensions: L4.rate\_hz (oscillation rate), L6.tempo\_bpm (motor timing), X18.motor\_cortex (Beta/Gamma). Brain regions: M1, SMA, Auditory Cortex.

\subsubsection{Tier $\gamma$ Models: STU Speculative Models}

\textbf{$\gamma$.1 Tempo Memory Reproduction Method (TMRM):}

Sensory support enhances tempo memory accuracy compared to motor-only reproduction. The TMRM model demonstrates that tempo adjusting (with sensory feedback) produces higher accuracy ($d=2.76$) than tempo tapping (motor only). Optimal tempo range: $\sim$120 BPM ($d=0.58$). Expertise effect: $d=0.59$. Evidence: Vigl 2024.

\textbf{$\gamma$.2 Neural Entrainment-Working Memory Dissociation (NEWMD):}

Paradoxical finding: stronger neural entrainment (SS-EP) correlates with worse tapping performance ($\beta = -0.060$), while higher working memory (Counting Span) correlates with better tapping ($\beta = 0.068$). This dissociation suggests that automatic beat-based predictions may reduce flexibility for active rhythm production. Evidence: Noboa 2025 ($n=30$, $p=0.006$).

\textbf{$\gamma$.3 Music Training Neural Efficiency (MTNE):}

Music training improves executive function with stable or decreased neural activation, suggesting enhanced neural efficiency rather than compensation.

\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}llccc@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Source} & \textbf{Finding} & \textbf{ES} & \textbf{n} & \textbf{p} \\
\midrule
Kosokabe 2025 & Music $\rightarrow$ inhibition $\uparrow$ & \cohend{0.60} & 57 & $<$0.004 \\
Kosokabe 2025 & Control $\rightarrow$ PFC $\uparrow$; Music $\rightarrow$ PFC stable & \cohend{0.04} & 57 & -- \\
Kosokabe 2025 & DCCS $\leftrightarrow$ VLPFC: $r=-0.57$ & \cohend{1.39} & 27 & $<$0.002 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\textbf{$\gamma$.4 Piano Training Grey Matter Plasticity (PTGMP):}

Piano training in older adults increases grey matter volume in bilateral DLPFC and right cerebellum, suggesting structural neuroplasticity even in aging brains.

\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lccc@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Finding} & \textbf{ES} & \textbf{n} & \textbf{p} \\
\midrule
DLPFC + cerebellum GMV $\uparrow$ & \cohend{0.34} & 25 & $<$0.05 \\
Frontal theta $\uparrow$ during improvisation & \cohend{0.27} & 40 & $<$0.024 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\textbf{$\gamma$.5 Musical Prodigy Flow State (MPFS):}

Musical prodigies are not distinguished by cognitive traits (IQ, working memory) but by propensity to experience flow during practice. Extraversion correlates with early practice initiation ($r=0.47$, $p<0.004$, $n$=54).

\subsection{Integrative Memory Unit (\IMU{})}

\subsubsection{Neural Substrates}

The \IMU{} exhibits the largest evidence base (213 studies) and encompasses memory systems from encoding through long-term consolidation:

\textbf{Hippocampal System:} The hippocampus ($n$=88) represents the most frequently cited region, reflecting its central role in binding musical elements with autobiographical context. Hippocampal activation increases for familiar versus novel music and for personally meaningful selections.

\textbf{Motor Memory:} The supplementary motor area ($n$=67) and primary motor cortex ($n$=21) contribute to procedural musical memory, including performance skills and implicit rhythm learning.

\textbf{Auditory Processing:} Superior temporal gyrus ($n$=26), auditory cortex ($n$=21), A1 ($n$=18), and Heschl's gyrus ($n$=8) support perceptual encoding of musical features that form the basis for memory traces.

\textbf{Executive and Self-Referential:} Anterior cingulate cortex ($n$=17), medial prefrontal cortex ($n$=14), and the default mode network ($n$=8) are implicated in self-referential processing and evaluation of personal significance.

\textbf{Emotional Binding:} Amygdala ($n$=12) and emotional processing regions contribute to the affective tagging of musical memories.

\subsubsection{Effect Sizes}

Random-effects meta-analysis of 60 quality-filtered effect sizes (Cohen's $d$ only, $|d|<2$) yielded a pooled \cohend{0.53} [95\% CI: 0.42--0.65; 95\% PI: --0.25 to 1.31] for memory-related contrasts. Heterogeneity was substantial (\Isquared{}=95.8\%, \tausquared{}=0.15), reflecting diverse memory paradigms (recognition, recall, familiarity). The wide prediction interval (spanning negative to moderate positive effects) indicates high variability across future studies. Figure~\ref{fig:forest_imu} presents the forest plot.

