\subsubsection{Tier $\alpha$ Models: Music-Evoked Autobiographical Memory Network (MEAMN)}

\textbf{\Rthree{} Dimensional Mapping:}
\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{R³ Dimension} & \textbf{Role} & \textbf{Layer} \\
\midrule
X14.musical\_mnemonic\_memory & Primary output & X-layer (Cognitive) \\
X11.nostalgia\_intensity & Affective correlate & X-layer (Affective) \\
L8.valence & Emotional valence & L8 (Semantic) \\
L8.emotion\_category & Emotional category & L8 (Semantic) \\
L4.rate\_hz & Temporal encoding & L4 (Dimensional) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

The MEAMN model characterizes the neural and psychological basis for music's exceptional capacity to evoke autobiographical memories:

\begin{equation}
P(\text{AM}|\text{music}) = \sigma\left(\beta_0 + \beta_1 F + \beta_2 A + \beta_3 V + \beta_4 \text{Age}\right)
\label{eq:meam}
\end{equation}

where $F$ represents familiarity ($\beta_1 \approx 0.78$), $A$ denotes arousal, $V$ indicates valence, and Age refers to age at encoding. The model captures the ``reminiscence bump'' phenomenon.

\textbf{Key Evidence:}
\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lccc@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Finding} & \textbf{ES} & \textbf{n} & \textbf{p} \\
\midrule
Familiarity $\rightarrow$ AM vividness & \correlation{0.78} & -- & $<$0.01 \\
MPFC activation: familiar $>$ unfamiliar & significant & -- & $<$0.05 \\
Hippocampal binding for personally meaningful music & significant & -- & $<$0.001 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\textbf{Falsification Criteria:}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*, topsep=0pt, itemsep=0pt]
\item Hippocampal lesions should abolish music-evoked AM
\item Novel music should not evoke autobiographical memories
\item Reminiscence bump should not appear for music encoded in adulthood
\end{itemize}

