\subsubsection{Tier $\alpha$ Models: Musical Mnemonic Preservation (MMP)}

\textbf{\Rthree{} Dimensional Mapping:}
\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{R³ Dimension} & \textbf{Role} & \textbf{Layer} \\
\midrule
X14.musical\_mnemonic\_memory & Memory performance & X-layer (Cognitive) \\
X21.music\_identification\_accuracy & Recognition accuracy & X-layer (Behavioral) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

The MMP model characterizes the remarkable preservation of musical memory in Alzheimer's disease and other neurodegenerative conditions, proposing that procedural and emotional aspects of musical memory follow dissociable neural pathways that are differentially affected by pathology.

\textbf{Key Evidence:}
\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}llc@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Finding} & \textbf{Population} & \textbf{Implication} \\
\midrule
Music recognition preserved vs. verbal memory loss & AD patients & Dissociable systems \\
Procedural music memory intact & AD patients & Motor-based sparing \\
Personally meaningful music enhances recall & AD patients & MEAMN linkage \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\textbf{Clinical Application:} Music therapy protocols leveraging MMP principles show efficacy for mood improvement and autobiographical memory access in dementia populations.

\textbf{Falsification Criteria:}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*, topsep=0pt, itemsep=0pt]
\item AD patients should not show impaired procedural music memory
\item Novel music should not aid memory retrieval in AD
\end{itemize}

