\subsubsection{Tier $\alpha$ Models: Autonomic-Affective Coupling (AAC)}

The AAC model characterizes the relationship between central affective processing and peripheral physiological responses.

\textbf{\Rthree{} Dimensional Mapping:}
\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{R³ Dimension} & \textbf{Role} & \textbf{Layer} \\
\midrule
L8.arousal & Primary correlate & L8 (Semantic) \\
L6.tempo\_bpm & Acoustic driver & L6 (Hierarchical) \\
L4.rate\_hz & Perceptual input & L4 (Dimensional) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\textbf{Mathematical Formulation:}
\begin{equation}
CI = w_1 \cdot SCR + w_2 \cdot (HR_{\text{baseline}} - HR) + w_3 \cdot RespR + \varepsilon
\label{eq:aac}
\end{equation}

where $CI$ is chills intensity (0--1), $SCR$ is skin conductance response ($\mu$S), $HR$ is heart rate (bpm), and $RespR$ is respiration rate.

\textbf{Key Evidence:}
\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}llcc@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Source} & \textbf{Finding} & \textbf{ES} & \textbf{n} \\
\midrule
Salimpoor 2011 & Chills $\leftrightarrow$ ANS arousal composite & \cohend{0.71} & 8 \\
Egermann 2013 & Unexpected events $\rightarrow$ SCR$\uparrow$, HR$\downarrow$ & \cohend{2.5} & 25--50 \\
Egermann 2013 & High info content $\rightarrow$ SCR$\uparrow$, HR$\downarrow$, RespR$\uparrow$ & \cohend{6.0} & 50 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\textbf{Falsification Criteria:}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*, topsep=0pt, itemsep=0pt]
\item ANS-blocked individuals should report normal subjective emotion with absent physiological response
\item Slow tempo should reduce SCR/HR responses (testable via parametric manipulation)
\end{itemize}

