The PCCR model demonstrates that pitch class (chroma) representation in auditory cortex follows octave-equivalence principles, with repeating neural patterns across octave boundaries using EEG adaptation paradigms.

\textbf{Key Evidence (Briley 2013):}
\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lccc@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Finding} & \textbf{ES} & \textbf{n} & \textbf{p} \\
\midrule
Same-chroma adaptation effect & \cohend{0.56} & 16 & $<$0.024 \\
Octave equivalence confirmed & significant & 16 & $<$0.05 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\textbf{Falsification Criteria:}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*, topsep=0pt, itemsep=0pt]
\item Non-octave intervals should not show chroma-specific adaptation
\item Amusics should not show PCCR patterns
\end{itemize}

