\subsubsection{Tier $\alpha$ Models: Pythagorean Neural Hierarchy (PNH)}

\textbf{\Rthree{} Dimensional Mapping:}
\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{R³ Dimension} & \textbf{Role} & \textbf{Layer} \\
\midrule
L5.sensory\_consonance & Ratio complexity & L5 (Perceptual) \\
X14.bold\_signal\_change & Neural response & X-layer (Neural) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

The PNH model extends consonance processing to memory encoding, proposing that simple frequency ratios (Pythagorean intervals) receive preferential neural representation.

\textbf{Mathematical Formulation:}
\begin{equation}
\text{Neural\_Activation}(\text{interval}) \propto \log_2(\text{numerator} \times \text{denominator})^{-1}
\label{eq:pnh}
\end{equation}

Small-integer ratio intervals (2:1 octave, 3:2 fifth) activate hippocampal and auditory regions more strongly than complex-ratio intervals.

\textbf{Key Evidence:}
\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lcc@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Finding} & \textbf{ES} & \textbf{p} \\
\midrule
Consonant $>$ dissonant: hippocampus, A1 & significant & $<$0.0001 \\
Simple ratios: stronger neural response & significant & $<$0.01 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\textbf{Falsification Criteria:}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*, topsep=0pt, itemsep=0pt]
\item Complex-ratio intervals should not activate auditory cortex more than simple ratios
\item Non-Western tuning systems should show different hierarchy patterns
\end{itemize}

