\subsubsection{Tier $\beta$ Models: IMU Integrative Models}

\textbf{$\beta$.1 Rhythmic Auditory Stimulation Neuroplasticity (RASN):}

Rhythmic auditory stimulation induces neuroplastic changes in motor and sensory circuits, with therapeutic implications for gait rehabilitation in Parkinson's disease and stroke recovery. Four meta-analyses support the efficacy of rhythmically-cued motor rehabilitation.

\textbf{$\beta$.2 Predictive Memory Integration Model (PMIM):}

Musical sequences activate predictive coding mechanisms, with ERAN (Early Right Anterior Negativity) and MMN (Mismatch Negativity) responses reflecting hierarchical prediction error signals during unexpected harmonic progressions (ERAN/MMN review: multiple studies).

\textbf{$\beta$.3 Oscillatory Intelligence Integration (OII):}

Individual differences in musical aptitude correlate with neural oscillatory patterns and general fluid intelligence (Gf). DTI/MEG evidence demonstrates enhanced interhemispheric connectivity and alpha/theta coherence in musically trained individuals.

\textbf{$\beta$.4 Hippocampal-Cortical Memory Circuit (HCMC):}

Musical memory consolidation requires hippocampal-cortical dialogue during both encoding and retrieval phases, with distinct neural signatures for implicit (procedural) and explicit (declarative) musical memories (Pipeline data: hippocampus $n$=88, SMA $n$=67).

\textbf{$\beta$.5 RAS-Intelligent Rehabilitation Integration (RIRI):}

Integration of rhythmic auditory stimulation (RAS) with intelligent rehabilitation technologies (robotics, VR) creates closed-loop, adaptive therapy paradigms that enhance motor and cognitive recovery through multisensory integration and temporal coherence. The RIRI model extends RASN by integrating haptic feedback (robotics) and visual stimuli (VR) with rhythmic cues, creating temporal coherence across modalities. Meta-analysis evidence (Zhao 2025, $n$=968): RAS + VR + robotics $>$ RAS alone, demonstrating enhanced functional connectivity restoration in multisensory integration areas.

\textbf{$\beta$.6 Musical Syntax Processing in Broca's Area (MSPBA):}

Harmonic syntax violations (Neapolitan chords) elicit mERAN (magnetic ERAN) responses localized in Broca's area (BA 44) and its right-hemisphere homologue, indicating domain-general syntactic processing shared with language. Key finding (Nature Neuroscience 2001, $n$=6, $p$=0.005): Position 5 (Neapolitan violation) elicits mERAN responses 100\% larger than Position 3 (in-key chords), with spatial separation from P2m (2.5 cm anterior, 1.0 cm superior to Heschl's gyrus). This demonstrates that musical syntax processing shares neural substrates with linguistic syntax, supporting domain-general syntactic computation.

\textbf{$\beta$.7 VR-Induced Analgesia Active-Passive (VRIAP):}

Active VR mode (motor interaction with music) shows better analgesic effect than passive mode (listening only) through enhanced visual-sensorimotor cortical activation and reduced pain processing connectivity. Active mode ($n$=15): Visual-sensorimotor activation significantly higher ($t$=2.59--3.99, $p<0.001$--0.015), S1 connectivity significantly lower ($t$=-4.64 to -3.53, $p$=0.029--0.049), resulting in highest pain reduction. Passive mode shows moderate activation and higher connectivity, with lower analgesic efficacy. Brain regions: Premotor, Somatosensory, Occipital cortex.

\textbf{$\beta$.8 Tonotopy-Pitch Representation Dissociation (TPRD):}

Primary regions within Heschl's gyri (HGs) exhibit more tuning to spectral content (tonotopy), whereas areas surrounding HGs exhibit more tuning to pitch (fundamental frequency), revealing distinct representations of tonotopy and pitch in auditory cortex. Primary HGs: Frequency-specific organization, physical acoustic properties (spectral content). Nonprimary HGs: Perceptual pitch representation, abstract frequency organization. This dissociation reveals a hierarchical transformation from physical (spectral) to perceptual (pitch) representations across auditory cortex ($n$=10).

\textbf{$\beta$.9 Cross-Modal Action-Perception Common Code (CMAPCC):}

Cross-modal classification reveals common neural representations of pitch sequences across perception and action in right premotor cortex, indicating emergence of a unified code for musical sequences. During learning, both perception (listening) and action (playing) create sequence-specific representations in auditory-motor regions. Right premotor cortex shows cross-modal classification: patterns generalize across conditions, indicating a common code for perception and action. This unified representation supports the hypothesis that music perception and production share fundamental neural substrates.

\subsubsection{Tier $\gamma$ Models: IMU Speculative Models}

\textbf{$\gamma$.1 Developmental Music Memory Scaffold (DMMS):}

Early musical exposure (neonatal, infant) establishes memory scaffolds that influence lifelong auditory-emotional associations. Neonatal care studies ($n$=1500, 56 studies) demonstrate music improves physiological responses, sleep quality, and cortisol levels, though long-term neurodevelopmental implications remain to be established.

\textbf{$\gamma$.2 Cross-Species Song Learning (CSSL):}

Song learning in birds (e.g., zebra finch) shares neural mechanisms with human musical memory, suggesting evolutionarily conserved memory systems. HVC (avian) shows functional homology with hippocampus (human). Key finding: tutees who share both melody AND rhythm of tutor's song show rhythm copying $r=0.94$ ($n$=37, $p<0.01$).

\textbf{$\gamma$.3 Context-Dependent Emotional Memory (CDEM):}

Musical emotional memories are context-dependent, with cross-modal information (visual, tactile) modulating encoding and retrieval strength. Multimodal study ($n$=84): arousal suppressed by benign video context ($d=0.17$, $p<0.0001$); valence less affected ($d=0.08$, $p<0.016$).

\subsection{Affective Resonance Unit (\ARU{})}

\subsubsection{Neural Substrates}

The \ARU{} encompasses the smallest but most effect-rich evidence base (42 studies, 87 claims), focusing on emotional and reward processing:

\textbf{Motor-Affective Interface:} Supplementary motor area ($n$=11) and superior temporal gyrus ($n$=7) link perceptual processing with affective responses.

\textbf{Reward System:} Nucleus accumbens ($n$=5), ventral striatum ($n$=4), caudate ($n$=4), and putamen ($n$=3) constitute the dopaminergic reward pathway activated during musical pleasure.

\textbf{Emotional Processing:} Amygdala ($n$=4), insula ($n$=4), and hippocampus ($n$=5) support rapid affective evaluation and emotional memory formation.

\textbf{Cognitive-Affective Integration:} Inferior frontal gyrus ($n$=4) and anterior cingulate cortex ($n$=3) mediate interactions between cognitive appraisal and emotional response.

\subsubsection{Effect Sizes}

Meta-analysis of 16 quality-filtered effect sizes (Cohen's $d$ only, $|d|<2$) yielded a pooled \cohend{0.83} [95\% CI: 0.61--1.05; 95\% PI: 0.05 to 1.61] for affective contrasts. Notably, heterogeneity was moderate (\Isquared{}=61.8\%, \tausquared{}=0.12), indicating relatively consistent affective responses to music across studies. The narrower prediction interval (compared to other units) reflects lower heterogeneity. Figure~\ref{fig:forest_aru} presents the forest plot.

Effect sizes ranged from $d$=0.05 to $d$=2.0, with a median of 0.84.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\resizebox{0.95\textwidth}{!}{%
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
    xlabel={Cohen's $d$},
    ylabel={Study},
    xmin=-0.5, xmax=2.5,
    yticklabels={},
    ytick=\empty,
    grid=major,
    width=14cm,
