\subsubsection{Tier $\alpha$ Models: Valence-Mode Mapping (VMM)}

The VMM model characterizes the systematic relationship between musical mode/consonance and valence-specific neural circuits.

\textbf{\Rthree{} Dimensional Mapping:}
\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{R³ Dimension} & \textbf{Role} & \textbf{Layer} \\
\midrule
L5.sensory\_consonance & Perceptual input & L5 (Sensory) \\
L8.valence & Affective output & L8 (Semantic) \\
L8.emotion\_category & Categorical output & L8 (Semantic) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\textbf{Neural Dissociation:} Happy music (major mode, consonant) preferentially activates ventral striatum (reward), dorsal striatum (approach), and ACC (reward evaluation). Sad music (minor mode, dissonant) preferentially activates hippocampus, amygdala, and parahippocampal gyrus (memory-emotion integration).

\textbf{Key Evidence (Mitterschiffthaler 2007):}
\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}llcc@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Contrast} & \textbf{Region} & \textbf{t(15)} & \textbf{p} \\
\midrule
Happy $>$ Neutral & Ventral Striatum & 4.58 & $<$0.001 \\
Happy $>$ Neutral & Dorsal Striatum (Caudate) & 4.12 & $<$0.001 \\
Happy $>$ Neutral & ACC (BA32/24) & 3.89 & $<$0.001 \\
Sad $>$ Neutral & Hippocampus/Amygdala (R) & 4.88 & $<$0.001 \\
Sad $>$ Neutral & STG (bilateral) & 4.21 & $<$0.001 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\textbf{Brain Region Dissociation:}
\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lccc@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Region} & \textbf{Happy} & \textbf{Sad} & \textbf{Function} \\
\midrule
Ventral Striatum & $\checkmark$ & -- & Reward \\
Amygdala & -- & $\checkmark$ & Emotional arousal \\
Hippocampus & -- & $\checkmark$ & Memory-emotion \\
ACC & $\checkmark$ & -- & Reward evaluation \\
STG & $\checkmark$ & $\checkmark$ & Auditory processing \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\textbf{Falsification Criteria:}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*, topsep=0pt, itemsep=0pt]
\item Major mode should not activate amygdala more than minor mode
\item Striatal lesions should reduce happy but not sad music appreciation
\end{itemize}

