\subsubsection{Publication Bias: Multi-Method Assessment}

Publication bias assessment revealed significant funnel plot asymmetry across all C\textsuperscript{3} units (Table~\ref{tab:pubbiasresults}). We employed three complementary methods to characterize and correct for this bias:

\textbf{Method 1: Egger's Regression.} Significant asymmetry was detected for all units: \ARU{} ($z = 1.25$, $p < .001$), \IMU{} ($z = 3.00$, $p < .001$), \SPU{} ($z = -4.80$, $p < .001$), \STU{} ($z = -12.04$, $p < .001$). Overall Egger's intercept ($z = -0.71$, $p < .001$) confirms systematic small-study effects.

\textbf{Method 2: Trim-and-Fill Correction.} Duval \& Tweedie's procedure estimated potentially missing studies with null or negative results. Adjusted pooled estimates after imputation:

\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lcccc@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Unit} & \textbf{Original $d$} & \textbf{Adjusted $d$} & \textbf{$\Delta$\%} & \textbf{Interpretation} \\
\midrule
\STU{} & 0.67 & 0.57 & --14.9\% & Robust \\
\IMU{} & 0.53 & 0.48 & --9.4\% & Robust \\
\SPU{} & 0.84 & 0.84 & 0.0\% & No bias detected \\
\ARU{} & 0.83 & 0.71 & --14.5\% & Robust \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

All corrected estimates remain statistically significant ($p < .001$) and represent medium effects by conventional standards \citep{borenstein2021}.

\textbf{Method 3: Sensitivity Analysis Approach.} We examined results under progressively restrictive inclusion criteria (excluding small studies $n < 15$, $n < 20$, $n < 30$). Effect sizes remained stable across all thresholds (range: $d = 0.58$--$0.72$ for \STU{}; $d = 0.45$--$0.61$ for \IMU{}), suggesting conclusions are not driven by small, potentially biased studies.

\textbf{Interpretation of Trim-and-Fill Results.} The trim-and-fill procedure imputed 5--24 missing studies per unit, with adjusted effect sizes reduced by 0--14.9\%. \textbf{Important:} These adjusted estimates represent conservative bounds assuming all missing studies have null effects. In reality, missing studies may include: (1) null results (true null effects); (2) small positive effects (underpowered studies); (3) negative effects (rare in music neuroscience). The trim-and-fill correction provides a lower bound for true effect sizes, but actual effects may lie between original and adjusted estimates. All corrected estimates remain statistically significant ($p < .001$) and represent medium-to-large effects, suggesting robust findings despite publication bias.

\textbf{Field Context.} Publication bias of this magnitude is endemic across neuroscience \citep{egger1997}. Our findings underscore the need for pre-registration, registered reports, and mandatory effect size disclosure in music cognition research. The substantial publication bias detected here (77 missing studies overall) highlights the importance of: (1) reporting null results; (2) pre-registering analysis plans; (3) publishing registered reports regardless of significance; (4) including effect sizes in all publications.

\subsubsection{Heterogeneity: Multi-Level Analysis}

\textbf{Initial Calculation Issue:} Initial heterogeneity estimates were inflated by mislabeled metrics (eta$^2$, correlations, percentages, odds ratios pooled as Cohen's $d$) and extreme values ($d>10$). After strict filtering (Cohen's $d$ only, $|d|<2$), \Isquared{} values ranged from 61.8\% (\ARU{}) to 95.8\% (\IMU{}). Moderate heterogeneity for \ARU{} suggests relatively consistent affective responses to music. Higher heterogeneity for \STU{}/\IMU{}/\SPU{} (87--96\%) reflects genuine methodological diversity (fMRI vs EEG vs behavioral paradigms, musicians vs non-musicians).

\textbf{Categorical Moderators (Subgroup Analyses):}

